(verb
  :name "geom/arcsin"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/arcsin x) -> radians"
  :summary "Inverse sine (arcsin) of x in radians, domain |x| ≤ 1."
  :explanation "Given a sine value x in [−1, 1], returns the angle in radians in [−π/2, π/2] (−90° to 90°) whose sine is x. Arcsin is the inverse of the sine function and recovers angles from vertical/transverse components. The result lies in the range [−π/2, π/2], making it the natural choice for finding angles in the \"principal\" range. Convert to degrees with geom/->degrees."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/arcsin 1)" :note "arcsin(1) = π/2 ≈ 1.57 radians (90°).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((angle-rad (geom/arcsin 0.866)))\n  (geom/->degrees angle-rad))" :note "arcsin(0.866) ≈ π/3 radians; convert to degrees to get ≈ 60°.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (elevation-angle distance height)\n  (let ((sin-angle (/ height distance)))\n    (geom/->degrees (geom/arcsin (max -1 (min 1 sin-angle))))))\n(elevation-angle 100 50)" :note "Find elevation angle from horizontal distance and vertical height; clamp to prevent domain errors.")
  )
  :caveats ("Domain is strictly [−1, 1]; inputs outside this range cause undefined behavior." "Output is restricted to [−π/2, π/2]; arcsin cannot directly find angles in the second or third quadrant." "Floating-point rounding may push values slightly outside [−1, 1]; always clamp before calling.")
  :drawbacks ("Limited to principal-range angles; for full [0, 2π) coverage, use geom/atan2 instead." "Slower than atan2 for general angle recovery from components." "Result is in radians; conversion to degrees is required for many applications.")
  :usecases ("Finding elevation or depression angle from height and distance." "Recovering angle from the sine of an angle (e.g., from component/magnitude ratio)." "Solving right triangles when the opposite side and hypotenuse are known." "Physics: computing launch angle from vertical velocity component.")
  :related ("geom/arccos" "geom/arctan" "geom/atan2" "geom/sin" "geom/->degrees" "geom/solve-right")
  :learn (:concept "Inverse trigonometric function: recover angle from sine value in principal range." :prerequisites ("geom/sin" "geom/->degrees") :progression "After arcsin, learn geom/atan2 to handle angles in all quadrants; then explore geom/law-of-sines-side for general triangle solving.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A projectile is launched with known vertical speed component and known total speed; the operator needs its launch angle above the horizontal." :program "(define (launch-angle vy speed)
  (geom/arcsin (max -1 (min 1 (/ vy speed)))))
(geom/->degrees (launch-angle 5 10))" :explanation "Ratio vy/speed is the sine of the launch angle. Clamp it to protect against float noise, then arcsin to get the angle in radians." :meta "geom/arcsin is the correct verb because the input is a sine value (opposite/hypotenuse ratio). arccos would be wrong — that would answer 'what angle has this cosine?' — a different question.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: inverse function on a principal branch, recovering an angle from a ratio."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/arcsin 0.5)")
       (:domain "elevator floor tracking (a metaphor domain — you know the height traveled; find the floor)" :code "(define (floor-from-height h floor-h) (round (/ h floor-h)))")
       (:domain "math — principal-branch inverse in [-π/2, π/2]" :code "(define (principal-angle s) (min (max s -1) 1))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung takes a ratio/scalar and recovers a parameter on a canonical branch."
     :meta "The shape transfers because inverting a periodic scalar map always requires a branch choice; arcsin picks [-π/2, π/2].")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applied to sine of an angle in the principal range, arcsin returns the original angle." :program "(define (test t) (< (abs (- (geom/arcsin (sin t)) t)) 1e-9))
(and (test 0.3) (test -0.8) (test 1.5))" :invariant "∀ θ ∈ [-π/2, π/2]. arcsin(sin(θ)) = θ" :meta "Left inverse on the principal branch. If broken outside the principal range, the branch is being extended incorrectly. See book-of-math ch 5.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
