  (let ((theta (geom/arcsin (/ vy speed))))
    (list 'launch theta 'apex (* speed (sin theta)))))
(aim 5 10)" :emergent "inverse-solver: measurement of one derived quantity recovers the parameter that generated it." :meta "Belongs to the family of inverse problems: given effect, recover cause. See book-of-composition ch 14 (recovery patterns).")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/arctan"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/arctan x) -> radians"
  :summary "Inverse tangent (arctan) of x in radians."
  :explanation "Given a tangent value x (any real number), returns the angle in radians in (−π/2, π/2) (−90° to 90°, exclusive) whose tangent is x. Arctan is the inverse of the tangent function. Unlike geom/arcsin and geom/arccos, the domain of arctan is all real numbers. However, like arcsin, the output is restricted to the principal range [−π/2, π/2], so it is best for \"mostly horizontal\" angles. For angles in all quadrants, use geom/atan2 instead."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/arctan 1)" :note "arctan(1) = π/4 ≈ 0.785 radians (45°).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((angle-rad (geom/arctan 0.577)))\n  (geom/->degrees angle-rad))" :note "arctan(0.577) ≈ π/6 radians; convert to degrees to get ≈ 30°.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (slope-angle rise run)\n  (if (= run 0)\n      (if (> rise 0) 90 -90)\n      (geom/->degrees (geom/arctan (/ rise run)))))\n(slope-angle 10 5)" :note "Convert slope (rise/run) to angle in degrees; handle vertical case separately to avoid division by zero.")
  )
  :caveats ("Output is restricted to (−π/2, π/2); arctan cannot distinguish between angles in opposite quadrants (e.g., 30° and 210°)." "For angles in all four quadrants, use geom/atan2 instead, which takes both y and x components." "Tangent has vertical asymptotes at ±π/2; arctan approaches these limits but never reaches them." "Be careful with rise/run slope: arctan(rise/run) fails when run=0 (vertical slope).")
  :drawbacks ("Limited to principal-range angles; use geom/atan2 for full directional recovery." "Slope-based workflows: arctan loses quadrant information without careful bookkeeping." "Result is in radians; conversion to degrees required for most applications.")
  :usecases ("Finding angle from slope (rise/run) when both are positive or the angle is mostly horizontal." "Solving for angle in arctangent-specific equations (e.g., projectile motion)." "Recovering angle from tangent value in theoretical or mathematical contexts." "Debugging: simple angle estimation when full quadrant info is not needed.")
  :related ("geom/arcsin" "geom/arccos" "geom/atan2" "geom/tan" "geom/->degrees" "geom/slope")
  :learn (:concept "Inverse tangent: recover angle from slope or tangent value in principal range." :prerequisites ("geom/tan" "geom/->degrees") :progression "After arctan, learn geom/atan2 to handle all four quadrants; then explore geom/solve-right and geom/law-of-sines-side for triangle problems.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A slope is given as rise-over-run; the operator needs the incline angle." :program "(define (slope-to-angle rise run)
  (geom/->degrees (geom/arctan (/ rise run))))
(slope-to-angle 1 1)" :explanation "Compute the ratio, apply arctan, convert to degrees for display." :meta "geom/arctan is the correct verb when you have a pure ratio and know the sign will not cross a quadrant boundary. If run could be 0 or negative, use geom/atan2 instead — arctan cannot distinguish quadrants.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: inverse function recovering an angle from a scalar slope."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/arctan 1)")
       (:domain "hill grading (a metaphor domain — road slope percent from a survey)" :code "(define (grade-percent rise run) (* 100 (/ rise run)))")
       (:domain "math — arctan as the antiderivative giving angle from slope" :code "(define (slope->rad r) r)")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung converts a slope-like ratio to an angular quantity."
     :meta "The shape transfers because slope = tan(angle) is invertible on the principal branch (-π/2, π/2).")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applied to tan of an angle in (-π/2, π/2), arctan returns the original angle." :program "(define (test t) (< (abs (- (geom/arctan (tan t)) t)) 1e-9))
(and (test 0.4) (test -0.5) (test 1.2))" :invariant "∀ θ ∈ (-π/2, π/2). arctan(tan(θ)) = θ" :meta "Left inverse on the principal branch. If broken, the impl is not clamping to the principal range. See book-of-math ch 5.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Convert slope to angle to drive an inclined-plane physics decision." :composition "(define (incline-force slope mass g)
  (let ((theta (geom/arctan slope)))
    (* mass g (sin theta))))
(incline-force 0.5 10 9.81)" :emergent "physical-mapping: geometric slope becomes an angular parameter for a physics formula." :meta "Belongs to the family of geometry-to-physics adapters. See book-of-composition ch 11 (adapter patterns).")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/atan2"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/atan2 y x) -> radians"
  :summary "Two-argument arctangent (atan2) of y and x, returns angle in all four quadrants."
  :explanation "Computes the angle θ in radians (in the range [−π, π]) such that tan(θ) = y/x, using both the sign and magnitude of y and x. This is the standard way to recover a full directional angle from (x, y) Cartesian components without losing quadrant information. atan2 avoids the singularity of division by zero and automatically handles the four quadrants. Converts to degrees with geom/->degrees. This is the workhorse for angle recovery in most geometry and physics tasks."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/atan2 1 1)" :note "atan2(1, 1) = π/4 ≈ 0.785 radians (45°, northeast).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((dx 10)\n      (dy 20))\n  (let ((angle (geom/atan2 dy dx)))\n    (geom/->degrees angle)))" :note "Angle from displacement vector (dx, dy) in degrees; correctly handles all four quadrants.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define my-sprite 'my-sprite)\n(define (point-toward-target entity target-x target-y)\n  (let* ((ex (entity/x entity))\n         (ey (entity/y entity))\n         (dx (- target-x ex))\n         (dy (- target-y ey))\n         (angle (geom/atan2 dy dx)))\n    (entity/set! entity 'facing (geom/->degrees angle))))\n(point-toward-target my-sprite 200 150)" :note "Set entity facing angle toward target; atan2 handles all directions without special cases.")
  )
  :caveats ("Argument order is (y, x), not (x, y); reversed order will give perpendicular angle." "Returns angle in [−π, π] radians; angles near ±π represent nearly opposite directions." "Both arguments can be zero, but atan2(0, 0) is typically 0 (or undefined per language); behavior may vary." "Result is in radians; use geom/->degrees for degree output.")
  :drawbacks ("Slightly slower than a single arctan call, but vastly more robust and avoids manual quadrant bookkeeping." "Not suitable for inverse tangent of pure ratios if you only care about magnitude (use geom/arctan instead)." "No direct way to get the \"wrapped\" angle difference; requires geom/angle-between or custom logic.")
  :usecases ("Converting (x, y) screen or world coordinates to a direction angle (e.g., for sprite rotation)." "Computing heading from velocity or displacement vectors." "Aiming: finding the angle from shooter to target in any direction." "Encoding direction in any 2D coordinate system (navigation, graphics, physics).")
  :related ("geom/arctan" "geom/arcsin" "geom/arccos" "geom/angle-between" "geom/->degrees" "geom/distance" "geom/slope")
  :learn (:concept "Full-range angle recovery from (y, x) components using two-argument arctangent." :prerequisites ("geom/->degrees") :progression "After mastering atan2, learn geom/sin and geom/cos to move in that direction; then geom/angle-between for angle differences, and geom/solve-right for triangle solving.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A player fires a projectile; the operator needs the angle from shooter position to target position, correct in every quadrant." :program "(define (aim-angle sx sy tx ty)
  (geom/atan2 (- ty sy) (- tx sx)))
(geom/->degrees (aim-angle 0 0 -3 -4))" :explanation "Subtract shooter from target to get displacement, then atan2(dy, dx) gives the correct full-range angle." :meta "geom/atan2 is the correct verb because atan (arctan) collapses quadrants: it cannot distinguish (dx=1,dy=1) from (dx=-1,dy=-1). atan2 preserves quadrant information from the signs of both arguments.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: full-range angle recovery from two orthogonal components."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/atan2 1 1)")
       (:domain "compass bearings (a metaphor domain — heading from N-S and E-W offsets)" :code "(define (bearing n-off e-off) (list 'n n-off 'e e-off))")
       (:domain "math — polar angle of a complex number a + bi" :code "(define (polar-angle a b) (list a b))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung takes a two-component vector and produces the direction it points in the plane."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'direction from two orthogonal components' is the same problem in every substrate that has orthogonal axes.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "atan2(sin θ, cos θ) recovers θ in [-π, π]." :program "(define (test t) (< (abs (- (geom/atan2 (sin t) (cos t)) t)) 1e-9))
(and (test 0.5) (test -1.0) (test 3.0))" :invariant "∀ θ ∈ [-π, π]. atan2(sin θ, cos θ) = θ" :meta "Full-range left inverse: unlike arctan, atan2 covers all four quadrants. If broken, quadrant selection is wrong. See book-of-math ch 5 (atan2 and quadrant recovery).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Convert a displacement vector into a facing angle for an entity." :composition "(define (face-target ex ey tx ty)
  (let ((theta (geom/atan2 (- ty ey) (- tx ex))))
    (geom/->degrees theta)))
(face-target 0 0 -1 -1)" :emergent "displacement-to-direction: a positional delta becomes a heading." :meta "Belongs to the family of directional-projection patterns: displacement → heading. Foundational for AI facing, camera aim, and navigation. See book-of-motion ch 5.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/circle"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/circle cx cy r) -> circle-record"
  :summary "Circle object of radius r centered at (cx, cy)."
  :explanation "Constructs a circle record (a structured representation) from a center point (cx, cy) and radius r. The circle object can be used with other geometric predicates and operations (e.g., collision detection, containment checks, distance queries). It is a lightweight, bitwise-compiled value that encodes the circle's geometry. Often composed with predicates to test intersection or containment with other shapes or points."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/circle 50 50 20)" :note "Create a circle centered at (50, 50) with radius 20.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((c1 (geom/circle 100 100 30))\n      (c2 (geom/circle 150 100 25)))\n  (let ((dist (geom/distance 100 100 150 100)))\n    (if (<= dist (+ 30 25)) 'overlapping 'separate)))" :note "Build two circles and check if they overlap by comparing center distance to sum of radii.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (spawn-exclusion-zone center-x center-y radius danger-level)\n  (let ((zone (geom/circle center-x center-y radius)))\n    (world/spawn 'danger zone 'level danger-level)))\n(spawn-exclusion-zone 200 200 50 'high)" :note "Create a circle object and embed it in a world entity for collision or proximity queries.")
  )
