(verb
  :name "geom/circle-area"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/circle-area r) -> area"
  :summary "Area of a circle with radius r; returns π r²."
  :explanation "Computes the area enclosed by a circle of radius r using the formula A = π r². The area grows quadratically with radius, so small changes in radius cause significant changes in area. Useful for collision detection (area occupied), resource calculations (coverage), and geometric reasoning about circular regions."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/circle-area 10)" :note "Area of circle with radius 10: π × 10² ≈ 314.16.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((radius 5))\n  (let ((area (geom/circle-area radius))\n        (circumference (geom/circle-circumference radius)))\n    (list 'area area 'perimeter circumference)))" :note "Compute both area and circumference of the same circle for comparison.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (coverage-per-entity total-area num-entities)\n  (let ((entity-radius (geom/pythagoras-leg total-area (/ total-area num-entities))))\n    (geom/circle-area entity-radius)))\n(coverage-per-entity 1000 4)" :note "Divide total coverage area among entities; compute each entity's circular zone radius and area.")
  )
  :caveats ("Radius must be non-negative; negative radius produces undefined or nonsensical result." "Result is in square units; ensure radius and area units are compatible." "Floating-point arithmetic may introduce small rounding errors in the π constant.")
  :drawbacks ("Only gives area; does not return circumference or other properties. Use geom/circle-circumference separately." "Cannot invert easily: to find radius from area, requires division by π and square root (i.e., r = √(A/π))." "Requires the radius as input; if you have a circle record, extract the radius first.")
  :usecases ("Computing coverage area of a sensor or light source." "Checking if an entity occupies too much space (area constraint)." "Game design: calculating resource consumption or spawn capacity based on circular zones." "Physics: moment of inertia or rotational properties of circular bodies.")
  :related ("geom/circle" "geom/circle-circumference" "geom/sector-area" "const/pi")
  :learn (:concept "Quadratic scaling of area with radius in circles." :prerequisites ("geom/circle") :progression "After circle-area, learn geom/circle-circumference for perimeter, then geom/sector-area for partial circles.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A designer needs to size a pond by target surface area; they must compute what radius gives 100 sq m." :program "(define (radius-for-area a)
  (math/sqrt (/ a math/pi)))
(radius-for-area 100)" :explanation "Invert πr² = A → r = √(A/π). This uses circle-area's formula in reverse to design to a target." :meta "For the forward query (radius → area), geom/circle-area is the correct verb because the formula is closed-form. Iterating with any other method is wasteful.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: quadratic scaling — a scalar output grows as the square of a scalar input."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/circle-area 5)")
       (:domain "printing ink (a metaphor domain — ink for a page scales with the page area)" :code "(define (ink-cost side) (* side side 0.01))")
       (:domain "math — the general quadratic law y = k·x²" :code "(define (quadratic k x) (* k x x))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung is a quadratic map from a linear parameter to a scalar output."
     :meta "The shape transfers because area of any similar 2D shape family scales as the square of a defining linear parameter.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Doubling the radius quadruples the area." :program "(define a1 (geom/circle-area 3))
(define a2 (geom/circle-area 6))
(< (abs (- a2 (* 4 a1))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ r > 0. circle-area(2r) = 4 · circle-area(r)" :meta "Homogeneous of degree 2 in radius. If broken, the exponent is wrong or the coefficient drifted. See book-of-math ch 4 (area of a circle).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Compute area for capacity-planning by chaining with a density." :composition "(define (fish-cap radius fish-per-sqm)
  (* (geom/circle-area radius) fish-per-sqm))
(fish-cap 5 3)" :emergent "capacity-model: area × density → capacity." :meta "Belongs to the family of first-order capacity models: area/volume × density → total. Same family as calorie counting from serving size. See book-of-composition ch 10.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/circle-circumference"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/circle-circumference radius) -> device-float"
  :summary "Compute the circumference of a circle given its radius."
  :explanation "The circumference of a circle is the distance around its perimeter, equal to 2πr where r is the radius. This verb takes a single numeric radius and returns the circumference as a device-float. It's the dual of geom/circle-area and is useful when you know the radius and need the perimeter for layout, collision bounds, or geometric calculations."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/circle-circumference 5)" :note "Circle with radius 5 has circumference ≈ 31.416")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((radius 10))\n  (list 'area (geom/circle-area radius)\n        'circumference (geom/circle-circumference radius)))" :note "Compare area and circumference for the same radius in one structure")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (scale-circle-by-circumference target-circ current-radius)\n  (let ((current-circ (geom/circle-circumference current-radius)))\n    (/ target-circ current-circ)))\n(scale-circle-by-circumference 62.832 5)" :note "Calculate the scaling factor needed to reach a target circumference")
  )
  :caveats ("Radius must be a non-negative number; negative radius returns negative circumference (which may be unexpected)" "Uses device-float precision; very large radii may lose precision" "Result is always a real number; no special handling for infinity or NaN inputs")
  :drawbacks ("If you need diameter instead of radius, convert first: (geom/circle-circumference (/ diameter 2))" "For arc length of a circle sector, use geom/arc-length instead")
  :usecases ("Layout: wrapping text or elements around a circular path" "Physics: computing perimeter bounds for collision detection" "Graphics: determining stroke lengths for concentric rings" "Geometry: validating or constructing circles from circumference measurements")
  :related ("geom/circle-area" "geom/circle" "geom/arc-length" "geom/perimeter")
  :learn (:concept "Circumference as the perimeter formula for circles; relationship between radius and arc length" :prerequisites ("const/pi" "number?") :progression "After mastering this, learn geom/circle-area (area formula), then geom/arc-length (partial circumference), then geom/sector-area (slice of circle)")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A designer needs to know the length of ribbon to wrap once around a circular column of radius r." :program "(define (ribbon-length r) (geom/circle-circumference r))
(ribbon-length 30)" :explanation "Direct application of the formula 2πr. The ribbon length is the circumference." :meta "geom/circle-circumference is the correct verb because it names the intent 'perimeter of a circle'. Using (* 2 math/pi r) works but hides intent from anyone reading the code.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: linear scaling — a scalar output grows in exact proportion to a scalar input."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/circle-circumference 10)")
       (:domain "wages (a metaphor domain — earnings scale linearly with hours worked)" :code "(define (earn hours rate) (* hours rate))")
       (:domain "math — the general linear law y = k·x" :code "(define (linear k x) (* k x))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung multiplies an input by a fixed constant to produce an output. Linear, not curved."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'proportional' is one of the two universal scalar laws; any first-order relationship shares this shape.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Doubling the radius doubles the circumference." :program "(define c1 (geom/circle-circumference 3))
(define c2 (geom/circle-circumference 6))
(< (abs (- c2 (* 2 c1))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ r > 0. circumference(2r) = 2 · circumference(r)" :meta "Homogeneous of degree 1 in radius. If broken, the formula was implemented with a bad exponent or coefficient. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Convert radius to circumference so a wheel can compute distance-per-revolution." :composition "(define (dist-per-rev radius) (geom/circle-circumference radius))
(define (odometer revs radius) (* revs (dist-per-rev radius)))
(odometer 100 0.35)" :emergent "cumulative-count: length per event × event count → total." :meta "Belongs to the family of tick-times-magnitude accumulators. Same family as bytes-per-page × pages. See book-of-composition ch 10.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/collinear?"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/collinear? point1 point2 point3) -> boolean"
  :summary "Test whether three points lie on the same straight line."
  :explanation "Three points are collinear if they all lie on a single line. This verb takes three point coordinates (each a list or pair of x,y values) and returns #t if they are collinear, #f otherwise. Collinearity is detected using bitwise operations on the cross-product calculation, making it a fast geometric predicate useful in polygon validation, line-segment tests, and triangle degeneracy checks."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/collinear? '(0 0) '(1 1) '(2 2))" :note "Points on the diagonal line y=x are collinear; returns #t")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((p1 '(0 0)) (p2 '(1 0)) (p3 '(1 1)))\n  (if (geom/collinear? p1 p2 p3)\n      'degenerate\n      'valid-triangle))" :note "Check whether three points form a degenerate (flat) triangle before computing area")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (valid-polygon? points)\n  (let loop ((pts points) (count 0))\n    (cond ((< (length pts) 3) (> count 0))\n          ((geom/collinear? (car pts) (cadr pts) (caddr pts)) #f)\n          (else (loop (cdr pts) (+ count 1))))))\n(valid-polygon? '((0 0) (1 0) (2 0) (3 0)))" :note "Validate that a polygon has no three consecutive collinear points")
  )
  :caveats ("Points must be given as two-element lists or pairs: (list x y)" "Numeric coordinates; string or non-numeric points will cause errors" "Uses bitwise operations: result may differ slightly from floating-point cross-product due to rounding strategy" "Order of points does not matter for collinearity; (p1 p2 p3) and (p3 p1 p2) give the same result")
  :drawbacks ("Does not tell you which point lies between the other two; use geom/distance to order them" "For testing if a point lies on a line segment (not just the infinite line), combine this with distance checks" "If checking many triples, consider precomputing a line equation instead of repeated calls")
  :usecases ("Polygon validation: detect degenerate triangles or flat vertices" "Path simplification: remove redundant waypoints that lie on straight segments" "Collision detection: check if a moving object passes through a line segment" "Geometry proofs: verify that configuration constraints hold (e.g., medians meet at centroid)")
  :related ("geom/similar?" "geom/triangle-area" "geom/distance" "geom/angle-between")
  :learn (:concept "Collinearity via cross-product; how zero area implies three collinear points" :prerequisites ("geom/triangle-area" "number?") :progression "After this, learn geom/triangle-area (compute signed area), then geom/angle-between (angle between rays), then geom/similar? (shape comparison)")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "Three GPS points come in; the operator wants to know whether they lie on one straight road segment or form a corner." :program "(define (is-corner? p1 p2 p3)
  (not (geom/collinear? p1 p2 p3)))
(is-corner? '(0 0) '(1 1) '(2 3))" :explanation "If the three points are collinear, they're on the same road. Otherwise they form a turn — treat as a corner." :meta "geom/collinear? is the correct verb because it uses a cross-product test (zero-area test) — robust for coordinates. Comparing slopes fails on vertical lines; this verb handles all orientations.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: zero-witness test — a value is checked to determine whether it lies on a lower-dimensional slice."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/collinear? '(0 0) '(1 1) '(2 2))")
       (:domain "checking receipts (a metaphor domain — three receipts summing to the same total = maybe a duplicate)" :code "(define (same-total? a b c) (and (= a b) (= b c)))")
       (:domain "math — a point lies on a linear subvariety iff a determinant is zero" :code "(define (linear-slice? d) (= d 0))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung tests whether a set of items collapses to a lower-dimensional relation."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'lies on a lower-dimensional slice' is the same predicate in every measured substrate.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "collinear? is invariant under permutation of the three points." :program "(define p1 '(0 0)) (define p2 '(1 1)) (define p3 '(2 2))
(and (equal? (geom/collinear? p1 p2 p3) (geom/collinear? p2 p3 p1))
     (equal? (geom/collinear? p1 p2 p3) (geom/collinear? p3 p1 p2)))" :invariant "∀ p1 p2 p3. collinear?(p1,p2,p3) = collinear?(σ(p1),σ(p2),σ(p3)) for any permutation σ" :meta "Symmetric predicate (invariant under S₃). If broken, the impl treats one point as special. See book-of-math ch 6 (invariance under permutation).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Test collinearity to filter a stream of point triples into corners and non-corners." :composition "(define (corners triples)
  (filter (lambda (t) (not (geom/collinear? (car t) (cadr t) (caddr t))))
          triples))
(corners '(((0 0) (1 1) (2 2)) ((0 0) (1 0) (0 1))))" :emergent "filter-predicate: a boolean test partitions a stream into two subsets." :meta "Belongs to the family of stream-partitioning patterns. Same family as WHERE clauses in SQL and filter in list processing. See book-of-composition ch 7.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/cone-surface"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/cone-surface radius slant-height) -> device-float"
  :summary "Compute the surface area of a cone given radius and slant height."
  :explanation "A cone's surface area comprises the base (a circle) and the lateral (side) surface. Given the base radius and the slant height (distance from apex to edge of base along the surface), this verb returns the total surface area as πr² + πrl, where r is radius and l is slant height. The slant height is distinct from the perpendicular height; if you have height h and radius r, compute slant height as √(h² + r²) first."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/cone-surface 3 5)" :note "Cone with radius 3 and slant height 5 has surface area ≈ 75.398")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((r 4) (h 3))\n  (let ((slant (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse h r)))\n    (geom/cone-surface r slant)))" :note "Calculate slant height from perpendicular height and radius, then surface area")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (cone-dimensions radius height)\n  (let ((slant (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse height radius)))\n    (list 'surface-area (geom/cone-surface radius slant)\n          'volume (geom/cone-volume radius height)\n          'slant-height slant)))\n(cone-dimensions 5 12)" :note "Bundle surface area, volume, and slant height for complete cone characterization")
  )
  :caveats ("The second argument must be slant height, not perpendicular height; confusion here is the most common error" "Both radius and slant height must be non-negative" "Slant height must be >= radius; otherwise the cone is geometrically impossible (returns NaN or negative area in edge cases)" "Uses device-float precision; very large dimensions may lose precision")
  :drawbacks ("Does not compute lateral surface area alone; if you need only the side surface, use (- (geom/cone-surface r l) (geom/circle-area r))" "If you have perpendicular height instead of slant height, you must precompute slant using geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse")
  :usecases ("Manufacturing: compute material needed for cone-shaped containers (ice cream cones, funnels)" "Architecture: surface area for cone-shaped roofs or domes" "Physics simulations: drag and heat-transfer calculations for conical objects" "Geometry: comparing surface area across different cone dimensions")
  :related ("geom/cone-volume" "geom/cylinder-surface" "geom/sphere-surface" "geom/circle-area" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse")
  :learn (:concept "Surface area formula for cones; distinction between slant height and perpendicular height" :prerequisites ("geom/circle-area" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse" "const/pi") :progression "After this, learn geom/cone-volume (volume formula), then geom/cylinder-surface and geom/sphere-surface (other solids), then geom/prism-volume")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A tent maker needs to know how much canvas to buy for a conical tent of given base radius and slant height." :program "(define (canvas r l waste-factor)
  (* (geom/cone-surface r l) waste-factor))
(canvas 3 5 1.15)" :explanation "Compute the total cone surface, multiply by a waste factor for cut-offs. The result is total material." :meta "geom/cone-surface is the correct verb because it includes the base and the lateral surface. Using only the lateral surface undercounts by a full circle.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: composite area — a total that is the sum of a base part and a lateral part."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/cone-surface 3 5)")
       (:domain "cake decoration (a metaphor domain — total frosting = top + sides)" :code "(define (frost top-a side-a) (+ top-a side-a))")
       (:domain "math — total area = ∑ of subregion areas" :code "(define (total-area xs) (apply + xs))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung sums two subregion measures to get a total."
     :meta "The shape transfers because area is additive over disjoint regions.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
