(verb
  :name "geom/cone-volume"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/cone-volume radius height) -> device-float"
  :summary "Compute the volume of a cone given base radius and perpendicular height."
  :explanation "The volume of a cone is one-third the volume of a cylinder with the same base and height: V = (1/3)πr²h. This verb takes the base radius and the perpendicular height (the vertical distance from apex to base center, not slant height) and returns the volume. It's useful for measuring capacity, comparing solid shapes, and solving packing problems."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/cone-volume 3 10)" :note "Cone with radius 3 and height 10 has volume ≈ 94.248")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((radius 4) (height 9))\n  (let ((cyl-vol (geom/cylinder-volume radius height))\n        (cone-vol (geom/cone-volume radius height)))\n    (list 'cylinder cyl-vol 'cone cone-vol)))" :note "Compare cone and cylinder volumes with same radius and height")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (similar-cones base-radius base-height scale-factor)\n  (let ((r (* base-radius scale-factor))\n        (h (* base-height scale-factor)))\n    (geom/cone-volume r h)))\n(list (similar-cones 2 5 1) (similar-cones 2 5 2) (similar-cones 2 5 3))" :note "Volumes of scaled cones show cubic relationship: scale by 2x → volume by 8x")
  )
  :caveats ("Height must be perpendicular (vertical), not slant height; slant height is used only for surface area" "Both radius and height must be non-negative" "Uses device-float precision; very large dimensions may overflow or lose precision" "A cone with zero height is degenerate and has zero volume")
  :drawbacks ("Does not give you surface area; use geom/cone-surface (with precomputed slant height) for that" "If scaling a cone, volume scales with the cube of the linear scale factor—easy to underestimate large cones")
  :usecases ("Container design: volume of cone-shaped cups, funnels, or silos" "Physics: gravitational or rotational calculations for cone-shaped objects" "Geometry: comparing volumes of cones vs. cylinders vs. pyramids" "Excavation/fill: volume of earth or sand in conical piles")
  :related ("geom/cone-surface" "geom/cylinder-volume" "geom/pyramid-volume" "geom/sphere-volume")
  :learn (:concept "Cone volume as one-third of cylinder; scaling relationships in 3D" :prerequisites ("geom/cylinder-volume" "const/pi" "number?") :progression "After this, learn geom/cylinder-volume and geom/pyramid-volume (related solids), then geom/prism-volume (generalized volumes)")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A traffic engineer needs to estimate the sand in a conical pile of given base radius and height." :program "(define (sand-volume r h) (geom/cone-volume r h))
(sand-volume 2 3)" :explanation "Direct application of V = (1/3)πr²h." :meta "geom/cone-volume is the correct verb because it uses the closed-form 1/3 relationship to a cylinder. Approximating via integration or slicing is wasteful for a right cone.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: volume as one-third of a bounding prism."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/cone-volume 3 6)")
       (:domain "ice-cream (a metaphor domain — three cone scoops equal one cylinder scoop in volume)" :code "(define (scoops-cyl cyl-v) (/ cyl-v 3))")
       (:domain "math — pyramid/cone volume = base·height/3" :code "(define (third-prism area h) (* area h 1/3))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung applies the 'one third of the enclosing prism' law."
     :meta "The shape transfers because for any solid tapering to a point on top of a fixed base, the calculus of slabs gives 1/3.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "A cone's volume is exactly one third of a cylinder with the same base and height." :program "(define r 4) (define h 9)
(define cone (geom/cone-volume r h))
(define cyl (geom/cylinder-volume r h))
(< (abs (- cone (/ cyl 3))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ r > 0, h > 0. cone-volume(r,h) = cylinder-volume(r,h) / 3" :meta "The 1/3 relationship is a monoid-homomorphism between two solid families. If broken, the coefficient drifted. See book-of-math ch 4 (solid volumes).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
