(verb
  :name "geom/cos"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/cos angle-degrees) -> device-float"
  :summary "Compute the cosine of an angle given in degrees."
  :explanation "Cosine is a trigonometric function that returns the ratio of the adjacent side to the hypotenuse in a right triangle. This verb takes an angle in degrees (not radians) and returns its cosine as a device-float between -1 and 1. It's the complementary function to geom/sin and is essential for angle-based calculations in physics, graphics, and geometry."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/cos 0)" :note "cos(0°) = 1")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((angle 45))\n  (list 'sin (geom/sin angle) 'cos (geom/cos angle) 'tan (geom/tan angle)))" :note "Compare all three primary trig functions for the same angle")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (point-on-circle center-x center-y radius angle-degrees)\n  (list (+ center-x (* radius (geom/cos angle-degrees)))\n        (+ center-y (* radius (geom/sin angle-degrees)))))\n(point-on-circle 10 20 5 60)" :note "Parametric point on a circle: x = cx + r·cos(θ), y = cy + r·sin(θ)")
  )
  :caveats ("Argument is in degrees, not radians—do not confuse with the native Scheme cos function" "Result is always between -1 and 1 (within floating-point precision)" "Very large angles (e.g., 1e10 degrees) may lose precision due to internal reduction" "No special handling for exactly 90° or 270° where cosine is theoretically zero but may return a tiny non-zero float")
  :drawbacks ("If you need radians, convert first with geom/->radians, then use a lower-level cosine function" "For inverse cosine (arccos), use geom/arccos instead")
  :usecases ("Graphics: rotating points and vectors around an origin" "Physics: computing force components along an axis" "Navigation: heading and bearing calculations" "Parametric paths: generating points along circles or waves")
  :related ("geom/sin" "geom/tan" "geom/arccos" "geom/->degrees" "geom/->radians")
  :learn (:concept "Cosine as adjacent/hypotenuse ratio; angle in degrees; periodicity of trig functions" :prerequisites ("geom/sin" "number?") :progression "After this, learn geom/sin (sine), then geom/tan (tangent), then geom/arccos (inverse cosine)")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A moving platform in a game oscillates horizontally; the operator needs to compute its x offset at time t seconds." :program "(define (platform-x t amp freq)
  (* amp (geom/cos (* freq t))))
(platform-x 0.5 100 90)" :explanation "Compute cos(freq·t) and scale by amplitude. The result is an oscillating x offset centered at zero." :meta "geom/cos is the correct verb because the angle is in degrees (Motoi convention). Using base Scheme's cos would require conversion — cleaner to use the geom-native version.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: bounded oscillation — a value cycles between -1 and 1 as a parameter increases."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/cos 60)")
       (:domain "tides (a metaphor domain — sea level oscillates over the day)" :code "(define (tide-level hour amp) (* amp (cos (* 15 hour))))")
       (:domain "math — sinusoid — periodic real function bounded in [-1, 1]" :code "(define (sinusoid t) (cos t))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung returns a value bounded in a fixed range, cycling with a periodic parameter."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'bounded periodic response' appears wherever a system oscillates.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "cos is periodic with period 360°: cos(θ + 360) = cos(θ)." :program "(define t 47.5)
(< (abs (- (geom/cos t) (geom/cos (+ t 360)))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ θ. cos(θ + 360) = cos(θ)" :meta "Periodicity is a fundamental invariant of the sinusoid. If broken, the internal angle reduction is wrong. See book-of-math ch 5 (periodicity).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain cos with time to produce oscillatory motion." :composition "(define (oscillate t)
  (list 'x (* 100 (geom/cos (* 90 t))) 'y (* 100 (geom/sin (* 90 t)))))
(oscillate 1)" :emergent "oscillator: time is converted to a bounded, periodic position." :meta "Belongs to the family of LFO/oscillator patterns: same family as audio LFOs and periodic animations. See book-of-motion ch 8.")
