(verb
  :name "geom/dilate"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/dilate point center scale-factor) -> point"
  :summary "Scale a point relative to a center point by a scale factor."
  :explanation "Dilation (or scaling) moves a point along the ray from the center, multiplying the distance by a scale factor. If the scale factor is > 1, the point moves away from the center; if < 1, it moves toward the center; if = 1, it stays put. Given a point, a center, and a scale factor k, this verb returns the dilated point. Dilation is a fundamental transformation in geometry, used for resizing shapes, creating similar figures, and coordinate transformations."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/dilate '(4 2) '(0 0) 2)" :note "Point (4, 2) scaled by 2× from origin becomes (8, 4)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((vertices '((1 0) (0 1) (-1 0) (0 -1))))\n  (map (lambda (pt) (geom/dilate pt '(0 0) 3)) vertices))" :note "Scale all vertices of a square by 3× to enlarge it")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (shrink-to-fit original-shape bounding-box-width)\n  (let* ((min-x (apply min (map car original-shape)))\n         (max-x (apply max (map car original-shape)))\n         (current-width (- max-x min-x))\n         (scale (/ bounding-box-width current-width))\n         (center-x (/ (+ min-x max-x) 2)))\n    (map (lambda (pt) (geom/dilate pt (list center-x 0) scale)) original-shape)))\n(shrink-to-fit '((0 0) (10 0) (10 5) (0 5)) 5)" :note "Scale a shape to fit a specified width, preserving its center")
  )
  :caveats ("Scale factor of 0 collapses all points to the center; negative scale factors reflect through the center" "Both point and center must be given as two-element lists: (list x y)" "Scale factor should be a number; non-numeric values will cause errors" "Uses device-float precision; accumulating many dilations can compound rounding errors")
  :drawbacks ("Does not preserve angles in non-uniform scaling (if you need different x and y scales, use a lower-level transform)" "Dilation of a large shape by a small scale factor may cause numerical underflow")
  :usecases ("Graphics: resizing UI elements or sprite art without changing position" "Geometry: constructing similar figures (same shape, different size)" "Animation: zoom-in and zoom-out effects relative to a point" "Layout: scaling a design from one bounding box to another")
  :related ("geom/translate" "geom/rotate" "geom/rotate-about" "geom/reflect-origin" "geom/transform-polygon")
  :learn (:concept "Dilation as scaling relative to a center; similarity transformations; preserving shape while changing size" :prerequisites ("geom/distance" "geom/translate") :progression "After this, learn geom/rotate and geom/rotate-about (rotation transformations), then geom/reflect-x/y (reflection), then geom/transform-polygon (combining transformations)")
