(verb
  :name "geom/distance"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/distance x1 y1 x2 y2) -> number"
  :summary "Euclidean distance between two points in the plane."
  :explanation "Returns the straight-line distance between (x1, y1) and (x2, y2) using the Pythagorean theorem: √((x2−x1)² + (y2−y1)²). This is the foundation for proximity checks, collision detection, and spatial queries. The result is a device float."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/distance 0 0 3 4)" :note "Returns 5.0 (the 3-4-5 right triangle).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (entity-near? ent1 ent2 radius)\n  (< (geom/distance (entity/x ent1) (entity/y ent1)\n                      (entity/x ent2) (entity/y ent2))\n     radius))" :note "Helper that checks if two world entities are within a radius.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (nearest-entity pos radius)\n  (let ((all-entities (world/find (lambda (e) #t))))\n    (fold-left (lambda (best e)\n                 (let ((d (geom/distance (car pos) (cdr pos)\n                                         (entity/x e) (entity/y e))))\n                   (if (< d radius)\n                       (if (or (null? best) (< d (car best)))\n                           (cons d e) best)\n                       best)))\n               null\n               all-entities)))" :note "Finds the nearest entity within radius using fold-left to track both distance and entity.")
  )
  :caveats ("Result is floating-point; use care when comparing distances for equality." "No bounds checking on arguments; invalid coordinates compute silently." "Does not account for wrapping or non-Euclidean geometry.")
  :drawbacks ("Square root is relatively expensive; if you only need to rank distances, square both arguments and compare squared distances instead." "For many proximity checks, consider spatial partitioning (grid or quadtree) to avoid O(n²) all-pairs distance computation.")
  :usecases ("Detecting when a projectile hits a target within a hit radius." "Finding the closest NPC to the player for interaction." "Sorting entities by distance for rendering or AI decision-making." "Implementing physics-based attraction or repulsion forces.")
  :related ("geom/midpoint" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse" "entity/distance" "world/nearest")
  :learn (:concept "The Euclidean metric as the canonical distance function in 2D space." :prerequisites ("Basic arithmetic (subtraction, squaring, addition)") :progression "After mastering distance, learn geom/angle-between to measure angular separation, and geom/collinear? to detect alignment.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A projectile must be tested for a hit on an enemy at (ex, ey); the operator needs to know how close the projectile is." :program "(define (hit? px py ex ey r)
  (< (geom/distance px py ex ey) r))
(hit? 100 100 105 103 10)" :explanation "Compute Euclidean distance; if less than the hit radius, count as a hit." :meta "geom/distance is the correct verb because it uses the standard √((Δx)²+(Δy)²) form and is device-optimized. Comparing squared distances is faster for ranking, but the named verb is fine for one-off checks and reads more clearly.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: metric — a scalar magnitude of separation between two structured items."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/distance 0 0 3 4)")
       (:domain "customer service (a metaphor domain — string-edit distance between typed name and known name)" :code "(define (edit-dist a b) (list 'from a 'to b)))")
       (:domain "math — norm-induced metric d(p,q) = ‖p−q‖" :code "(define (norm-distance p q) (sqrt (+ (expt (- (car p) (car q)) 2) (expt (- (cadr p) (cadr q)) 2))))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung produces a non-negative scalar reflecting how far apart two items are in the substrate's natural measure."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'distance' is defined wherever there is a norm.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Distance is symmetric: swapping the two endpoints yields the same distance." :program "(define d1 (geom/distance 0 0 3 4))
(define d2 (geom/distance 3 4 0 0))
(< (abs (- d1 d2)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ x1 y1 x2 y2. distance(x1,y1,x2,y2) = distance(x2,y2,x1,y1)" :meta "Metric symmetry (one of the three metric axioms). If broken, the impl squares the wrong difference. See book-of-math ch 4 (Euclidean metric).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain distance with a threshold to build a proximity trigger." :composition "(define (near? a b threshold)
  (< (geom/distance (car a) (cadr a) (car b) (cadr b)) threshold))
(near? '(0 0) '(2 2) 5)" :emergent "proximity-trigger: two positions and a scalar produce a boolean event." :meta "Belongs to the family of geofence patterns: same family as Bluetooth beacons, WiFi RSSI thresholds, spatial indices. See book-of-composition ch 12.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/inscribed-angle"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/inscribed-angle central-angle) -> number"
  :summary "Inscribed angle subtended by a central angle in a circle."
  :explanation "The inscribed angle theorem states that an inscribed angle is half the central angle that subtends the same arc. Given a central angle (in radians), returns the inscribed angle. This is useful for circle geometry, animation arcs, and spatial reasoning about angles on a circumference."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/inscribed-angle (geom/->radians 90))" :note "Central angle of 90° (π/2 rad) yields inscribed angle of 45° (π/4 rad).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (arc-wedge center-x center-y radius central-angle)\n  (let ((inscribed (geom/inscribed-angle central-angle)))\n    (list 'center (list center-x center-y)\n          'radius radius\n          'inscribed-angle inscribed)))" :note "Builds a circle arc descriptor pairing the inscribed angle with geometry.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (place-on-circle-arc center radius start-angle arc-spread count)\n  (let ((inscribed (geom/inscribed-angle arc-spread)))\n    (map (lambda (i)\n           (let ((theta (+ start-angle (* i inscribed))))\n             (list (+ (car center) (* radius (cos theta)))\n                   (+ (cdr center) (* radius (sin theta))))))\n         (let loop ((n 0) (acc null))\n           (if (= n count) (reverse acc)\n               (loop (+ n 1) (cons n acc)))))))" :note "Distributes points evenly around a circle arc using the inscribed angle spacing.")
  )
  :caveats ("Input and output are in radians; convert with geom/->degrees or geom/->radians if working in degrees." "Assumes the central angle is positive and typically in the range [0, 2π]." "No validation; passing a negative or very large angle computes silently.")
  :drawbacks ("This is a simple division; the theorem itself is not computationally expensive, but inscribed angles are less intuitive than central angles for many tasks." "For animation, you may want to work directly with central angles for clearer semantics.")
  :usecases ("Animating a point along a circle arc with consistent angular velocity." "Calculating viewing angles from points on a circle's circumference." "Geometric proofs and constructions involving cyclic polygons." "Creating circular UI elements with proportional spacing.")
  :related ("geom/interior-angle" "geom/arc-length" "geom/sector-area" "geom/->radians" "geom/->degrees")
  :learn (:concept "The inscribed angle theorem: a fundamental relationship in circle geometry." :prerequisites ("Understanding radians and degree-radian conversion" "Familiarity with circles and central angles") :progression "Build on this with geom/arc-length to compute actual distances along the arc, and geom/sector-area to compute the area swept by an arc.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "An artist places points evenly around a semicircular arc; each step must match the inscribed angle for a given central angle." :program "(define (inscribed-step central) (geom/inscribed-angle central))
(inscribed-step (/ math/pi 2))" :explanation "The inscribed angle equals half the central angle. Use it to space points along an arc." :meta "geom/inscribed-angle is the correct verb because it names the inscribed-angle theorem. Halving the central angle inline works but hides the theorem being applied.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: halving — an input's magnitude is exactly divided by two."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/inscribed-angle math/pi)")
       (:domain "splitting a bill (a metaphor domain — each of two friends pays half)" :code "(define (split total) (/ total 2))")
       (:domain "math — 1/2 scaling map: y = x/2" :code "(define (half x) (/ x 2))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung takes a scalar and returns its half."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'half' is a canonical scaling in any group where 2 is invertible.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Inscribed angle is exactly half the central angle." :program "(define c 1.2)
(< (abs (- (geom/inscribed-angle c) (/ c 2))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ central > 0. inscribed-angle(central) = central / 2" :meta "Direct linear scaling. If broken, the coefficient is not 1/2. See book-of-math ch 4 (inscribed-angle theorem).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain inscribed-angle with a loop to place vertices along an arc." :composition "(define (arc-vertices central-total count)
  (let ((step (geom/inscribed-angle central-total)))
    (list 'step step 'count count)))
(arc-vertices math/pi 5)" :emergent "arc-stepper: a total sweep is divided into equal inscribed-angle jumps." :meta "Belongs to the family of iterative-partition patterns: same family as evenly-spaced axis ticks in plotting. See book-of-composition ch 9.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/interior-angle"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/interior-angle n) -> number"
  :summary "Interior angle of a regular n-gon in radians."
  :explanation "For a regular polygon with n sides, all interior angles are equal. This verb returns that angle in radians. The formula is ((n − 2) × π) / n. Useful for constructing regular polygons, tiling, and understanding polygon properties."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/interior-angle 4)" :note "A square (4-gon) has interior angles of π/2 radians (90°).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (polygon-vertices n radius)\n  (let ((angle-step (geom/interior-angle n)))\n    (map (lambda (i)\n           (let ((theta (* i angle-step)))\n             (list (* radius (cos theta))\n                   (* radius (sin theta)))))\n         (let loop ((k 0) (acc null))\n           (if (= k n) (reverse acc)\n               (loop (+ k 1) (cons k acc)))))))" :note "Distributes n vertices around a circle using the interior angle as a stepping increment.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (tessellate-regular-grid side-length)\n  (let ((n 6) (interior (geom/interior-angle 6)))\n    (letrec ((row (lambda (x y rows-left)\n                    (if (= rows-left 0) null\n                        (let ((next-x (+ x side-length)))\n                          (cons (list 'hex x y interior)\n                                (row next-x y (- rows-left 1)))))))\n             (all-rows (lambda (y col-count rows-left)\n                         (if (= rows-left 0) null\n                             (append (row 0 y col-count)\n                                     (all-rows (+ y (* side-length 1.732)) col-count (- rows-left 1)))))))\n      (all-rows 0 5 10))))" :note "Generates a hexagonal tessellation using interior angle to verify hex geometry.")
  )
  :caveats ("Result is in radians; convert with geom/->degrees if you need degrees." "n must be at least 3; smaller values yield invalid or negative angles." "No validation; passing n < 3 returns a nonsensical result.")
  :drawbacks ("This computes the angle assuming a perfect regular polygon; real-world construction may suffer rounding errors." "For tiling or tessellation, you may need to work with exterior angles or turning angles instead.")
  :usecases ("Constructing regular polygons (hexagons, octagons) for tiles or UI." "Validating that a drawn polygon is regular." "Computing turning angles for path-drawing algorithms." "Designing symmetric artwork or patterns.")
  :related ("geom/interior-angle-deg" "geom/regular-polygon-vertices" "geom/regular-polygon-area" "geom/polygon-area" "geom/->degrees")
  :learn (:concept "The sum of interior angles in a polygon and how they distribute evenly in regular polygons." :prerequisites ("Understanding polygons and the relationship between sides and angles" "Basic geometry (sum of angles in a triangle = π)") :progression "Once comfortable with this, learn geom/regular-polygon-vertices to build the actual polygon and geom/regular-polygon-area to compute its area.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A CAD tool needs the interior angle of a regular hexagon to render its tile pattern." :program "(define (hex-angle) (geom/interior-angle 6))
(geom/->degrees (hex-angle))" :explanation "Apply the formula for n=6. Result is 2π/3 rad = 120°." :meta "geom/interior-angle is the correct verb because it encodes ((n-2)π/n) — a form that generalizes cleanly. Computing (2π/3) inline works for n=6 but obscures generality.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: closed-form combinatorial output — a formula produces a value from an integer parameter."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/interior-angle 6)")
       (:domain "polling (a metaphor domain — average vote share per party given n parties)" :code "(define (share n) (/ 100 n))")
       (:domain "math — closed-form recurrence solution" :code "(define (closed n) (/ (- n 2) n))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung produces a value from an integer via a closed formula."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'value from count' is a universal combinatorial idiom.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "As n → ∞ the interior angle approaches π." :program "(define big (geom/interior-angle 10000))
(< (abs (- big math/pi)) 1e-3)" :invariant "lim (n → ∞) interior-angle(n) = π" :meta "Limit of the polygon interior angle is a straight angle. If broken, the coefficient is wrong. See book-of-math ch 4 (regular polygons).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Feed interior-angle into a vertex-placer for a regular polygon." :composition "(define (regular-tiles n radius)
  (let ((a (geom/interior-angle n)))
    (list 'interior a 'n n)))
(regular-tiles 6 10)" :emergent "shape-descriptor: an integer count expands to a full shape description." :meta "Belongs to the family of generator-from-count patterns: same family as octree subdivisions. See book-of-composition ch 9.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/interior-angle-deg"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/interior-angle-deg n) -> number"
  :summary "Interior angle of a regular n-gon in degrees."
  :explanation "Same as geom/interior-angle but returns the result in degrees rather than radians. For a regular n-gon, the formula is ((n − 2) × 180) / n. This is often more intuitive for design and manual calculation."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/interior-angle-deg 6)" :note "A regular hexagon has interior angles of 120°.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (validate-regular-polygon sides measured-angle)\n  (let ((expected (geom/interior-angle-deg sides)))\n    (< (abs (- measured-angle expected)) 0.5)))" :note "Checks if a measured angle matches the expected interior angle (within 0.5°).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (build-path-polygon n start-x start-y side-length)\n  (let ((interior (geom/interior-angle-deg n))\n        (exterior (- 180 (geom/interior-angle-deg n))))\n    (letrec ((walk (lambda (step x y heading path)\n                     (if (= step n) (reverse path)\n                         (let ((next-x (+ x (* side-length (cos (geom/->radians heading)))))\n                               (next-y (+ y (* side-length (sin (geom/->radians heading)))))\n                               (next-heading (+ heading exterior)))\n                           (walk (+ step 1) next-x next-y next-heading\n                                 (cons (list next-x next-y) path)))))))\n      (walk 0 start-x start-y 0 (list (list start-x start-y))))))" :note "Walks out a regular polygon by turning exterior angle at each step and tracking the path.")
  )
  :caveats ("Result is in degrees; use geom/->radians if you need radians." "n must be at least 3 for a valid polygon." "No validation on n; passing invalid values returns nonsensical results.")
  :drawbacks ("Degrees are less standard in mathematics; many trigonometric functions expect radians." "Converting between degrees and radians adds a small computational cost; stick with radians if internal consistency is possible.")
  :usecases ("Designing UI or game art in degrees (more familiar to designers)." "Communicating angles to non-technical team members." "Validating user-drawn or measured polygons." "Educational contexts where degrees are the standard notation.")
  :related ("geom/interior-angle" "geom/->radians" "geom/->degrees" "geom/regular-polygon-vertices" "geom/regular-polygon-area")
  :learn (:concept "Interior angles in degrees; understanding the conversion and intuition of 180° and 360° reference points." :prerequisites ("Familiarity with degrees as an angle unit" "Knowing that the sum of interior angles is (n − 2) × 180°") :progression "After this, learn geom/->radians to convert to radians for trigonometric work, and geom/regular-polygon-vertices to build the polygon.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A tile designer works in degrees; they need the interior angle of a regular pentagon." :program "(define (pent-angle-deg) (geom/interior-angle-deg 5))
(pent-angle-deg)" :explanation "Apply the degree formula ((n-2)·180)/n. n=5 → 108°." :meta "geom/interior-angle-deg is the correct verb when the tool works in degrees. Converting from geom/interior-angle every time is possible but adds noise.")
