(verb
  :name "geom/law-of-cosines-angle"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/law-of-cosines-angle a b c) -> number"
  :summary "Find the angle opposite side c in a triangle given all three side lengths."
  :explanation "The law of cosines states that c² = a² + b² − 2ab·cos(C), where C is the angle opposite c. This verb solves for C: C = arccos((a² + b² − c²) / (2ab)). This is essential when you know all three sides and need to find an angle—or when you know two sides and the angle between them and need the third side (use geom/law-of-cosines-side for that). Returns angle in radians."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/law-of-cosines-angle 3 4 5)" :note "For a 3-4-5 right triangle, the angle opposite the hypotenuse (5) is π/2 (90°).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (triangle-angles a b c)\n  (let ((angle-C (geom/law-of-cosines-angle a b c))\n        (angle-A (geom/law-of-cosines-angle b c a))\n        (angle-B (geom/law-of-cosines-angle a c b)))\n    (list angle-A angle-B angle-C)))" :note "Computes all three angles of a triangle given three side lengths.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (classify-triangle a b c)\n  (let ((angle (geom/law-of-cosines-angle a b c))\n        (pi-half (* 2 (atan 1.0 1.0))))  ; π/2\n    (cond ((< angle pi-half) 'acute)\n          ((= angle pi-half) 'right)\n          (else 'obtuse))))" :note "Classifies a triangle by checking the largest angle (opposite longest side).")
  )
  :caveats ("Result is in radians; convert with geom/->degrees if needed." "Requires valid triangle inequality: a + b > c, a + c > b, b + c > a. No validation." "Floating-point rounding can cause arccos to receive values slightly outside [−1, 1], causing NaN or error. Be cautious with nearly-degenerate triangles." "Side order matters: c is the side opposite the returned angle.")
  :drawbacks ("Arccos is more expensive than some other operations; if you only need to rank angles, avoid taking arccos." "For right triangles, geom/solve-right may be simpler and faster." "If you know two sides and the included angle, use geom/law-of-cosines-side instead to find the third side.")
  :usecases ("Determining the angle at a vertex of a triangle when all three side lengths are known." "Detecting whether a triangle is acute, right, or obtuse." "Computing internal angles of polygons by triangulation." "Physics or collision detection: resolving contact normals and reflection angles.")
  :related ("geom/law-of-cosines-side" "geom/law-of-sines-side" "geom/solve-right" "geom/->degrees" "geom/triangle-area" "geom/triangle-area-heron")
  :learn (:concept "The law of cosines as a generalization of the Pythagorean theorem to arbitrary triangles." :prerequisites ("Understanding triangle properties and side-angle relationships" "Familiarity with arccos and its domain [−1, 1]") :progression "Master this, then learn geom/law-of-cosines-side to find sides when angles are known, and geom/law-of-sines-side for more complex scenarios.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A surveyor has three side measurements of a triangular plot and must find the angle at the corner opposite side c." :program "(define (corner a b c)
  (geom/->degrees (geom/law-of-cosines-angle a b c)))
(corner 5 7 9)" :explanation "Apply the law of cosines: C = arccos((a² + b² − c²) / (2ab)). Convert to degrees for the survey report." :meta "geom/law-of-cosines-angle is the correct verb because it's the only closed form for angle-from-three-sides. Iterating with law-of-sines would need extra info.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: inverse-formula recovery — three interlinked measurements let one be derived from the others."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/law-of-cosines-angle 3 4 5)")
       (:domain "weather (a metaphor domain — three pressure readings triangulate storm center)" :code "(define (triangulate a b c) (list 'from a b c)))")
       (:domain "math — Gram matrix inversion recovering angles from norm-and-inner data" :code "(define (gram-recover a b c) (list a b c))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung uses three known scalars to recover an angular relationship."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'three interlinked scalars determine an angle' is fundamental to triangulation.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applied to a right 3-4-5 triangle, the angle opposite the hypotenuse is π/2." :program "(< (abs (- (geom/law-of-cosines-angle 3 4 5) (/ math/pi 2))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ pythagorean triple (a,b,c). law-of-cosines-angle(a,b,c) = π/2" :meta "Special case of the general law: Pythagorean-triple test. If broken, the arccos or the sum-of-squares is misencoded. See book-of-math ch 4 (law of cosines).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain law-of-cosines-angle across all three angles to classify a triangle." :composition "(define (classify a b c)
  (let ((C (geom/law-of-cosines-angle a b c)))
    (cond ((> C (/ math/pi 2)) 'obtuse)
          ((< (abs (- C (/ math/pi 2))) 1e-6) 'right)
          (else 'acute))))
(classify 5 6 10)" :emergent "classifier: three measurements produce a category label." :meta "Belongs to the family of measurement-classifier patterns. See book-of-composition ch 12.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/law-of-cosines-side"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/law-of-cosines-side a b angle-C) -> number"
  :summary "Find the third side of a triangle given two sides and the included angle."
  :explanation "The law of cosines states that c² = a² + b² − 2ab·cos(C), where a and b are two sides and C is the angle between them. This verb solves for c directly. Given side lengths a and b and the angle C (in radians) between them, returns the length of the third side c opposite that angle."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/law-of-cosines-side 3 4 (geom/->radians 90))" :note "Two sides of 3 and 4 with a 90° angle between them yields the hypotenuse 5.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (diagonal-of-parallelogram a b angle)\n  (geom/law-of-cosines-side a b angle))" :note "A parallelogram's diagonal is the third side of a triangle formed by two adjacent sides and their included angle.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (construct-triangle a b angle-c-rad)\n  (let ((c (geom/law-of-cosines-side a b angle-c-rad))\n        (angle-a (geom/law-of-cosines-angle b c a))\n        (angle-b (geom/law-of-cosines-angle a c b)))\n    (list 'sides (list a b c)\n          'angles (list angle-a angle-b angle-c-rad)\n          'area (geom/triangle-area a b angle-c-rad))))" :note "Fully constructs a triangle given two sides and the included angle: computes the third side, other angles, and area.")
  )
  :caveats ("Input angle must be in radians; convert with geom/->radians if you have degrees." "Angle must be in the range (0, π) for a valid triangle; no validation." "Floating-point rounding can occur; results should be compared with tolerance rather than equality.")
  :drawbacks ("If you already have all three sides and just need an angle, use geom/law-of-cosines-angle instead (more direct)." "For right triangles with known hypotenuse and one leg, geom/pythagoras-leg is faster." "This is more general but slower than special-case formulas for specific triangle types.")
  :usecases ("Constructing a triangle from two known sides and their included angle (e.g., surveying or navigation)." "Computing the diagonal of a parallelogram." "Extending a path by turning at a known angle: given current segment and turn angle, compute the next segment length." "Physics: resolving forces in non-orthogonal coordinate systems.")
  :related ("geom/law-of-cosines-angle" "geom/law-of-sines-side" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse" "geom/solve-right" "geom/->radians" "geom/triangle-area")
  :learn (:concept "The law of cosines as a tool for constructing and analyzing arbitrary triangles given sides and angles." :prerequisites ("Understanding the law of cosines formula" "Familiarity with radians" "Knowing the relationship between a triangle's sides and angles") :progression "Next, learn geom/law-of-cosines-angle to solve the inverse problem, and geom/law-of-sines-side for scenarios where you don't have two sides adjacent to a known angle.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A land surveyor knows two side lengths and the included angle of a triangular field; they need the third side." :program "(define (third-side a b angle-deg)
  (geom/law-of-cosines-side a b (geom/->radians angle-deg)))
(third-side 10 12 60)" :explanation "Convert the included angle to radians, apply the law of cosines." :meta "geom/law-of-cosines-side is the correct verb because the input is SAS (side-angle-side). Law of sines would need at least one angle-side pair aligned differently.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: side-from-two-sides-and-included-angle recovery."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/law-of-cosines-side 5 7 (/ math/pi 3))")
       (:domain "physical linkage (a metaphor domain — two rigid arms at a joint, find the tip-to-tip length)" :code "(define (arm a1 a2 joint-a) (list a1 a2 joint-a)))")
       (:domain "math — cosine rule in an inner-product space" :code "(define (cosine-rule a b theta) (list a b theta))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung recovers a third length from two lengths and the angle they enclose."
     :meta "The shape transfers because any inner-product space has this relationship.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "At angle π/2 the law of cosines reduces to the Pythagorean theorem." :program "(define c (geom/law-of-cosines-side 3 4 (/ math/pi 2)))
(< (abs (- c 5)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ a,b. law-of-cosines-side(a,b,π/2) = √(a² + b²)" :meta "Pythagorean special case. If broken, the cos(π/2) is not evaluating to 0. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
