    (:base "Chain law-of-cosines-side to solve a complete triangle." :composition "(define (solve-sas a b angle-rad)
  (let ((c (geom/law-of-cosines-side a b angle-rad)))
    (list 'sides (list a b c) 'C angle-rad)))
(solve-sas 5 7 (/ math/pi 3))" :emergent "triangle-solver: partial data expands into a full solution record." :meta "Belongs to the family of missing-value recovery patterns. See book-of-composition ch 14.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/law-of-sines-side"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/law-of-sines-side a angle-A angle-B) -> number"
  :summary "Find side opposite angle B given side a opposite angle A and both angles."
  :explanation "The law of sines states that a/sin(A) = b/sin(B) = c/sin(C). Given a side length a, the angle A opposite it, and another angle B, this verb solves for the side b opposite B: b = a · sin(B) / sin(A). This is useful when you know one side and two angles (or can compute them)."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/law-of-sines-side 10 (geom/->radians 30) (geom/->radians 60))" :note "Side of length 10 opposite a 30° angle; find the side opposite a 60° angle.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (solve-triangle-asa side-a angle-at-a angle-at-b)\n  ;; ASA = Angle-Side-Angle; we know a, angle opposite to one end, and angle at other end\n  (let ((angle-c (- (geom/->radians 180) angle-at-a angle-at-b))\n        (b (geom/law-of-sines-side side-a angle-at-a angle-at-b))\n        (c (geom/law-of-sines-side side-a angle-at-a angle-c)))\n    (list 'sides (list side-a b c)\n          'angles (list angle-at-a angle-at-b angle-c))))" :note "Solves a triangle in ASA (Angle-Side-Angle) configuration using the law of sines twice.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (triangulate-landmark p1 p2 bearing-from-p1 bearing-from-p2)\n  ;; p1 and p2 are known survey points; bearings are angles from each point to an unseen landmark\n  (let ((distance-p1-p2 (geom/distance (car p1) (cdr p1) (car p2) (cdr p2)))\n        (angle-at-p1 bearing-from-p1)\n        (angle-at-p2 (- (geom/->radians 180) bearing-from-p2)))\n    (let ((side-to-landmark (geom/law-of-sines-side distance-p1-p2 angle-at-p1 angle-at-p2)))\n      (list 'distance-from-p1 side-to-landmark\n            'bearing bearing-from-p1))))" :note "Uses law of sines to triangulate an unseen landmark from two known survey points and their bearings.")
  )
  :caveats ("All angles must be in radians; convert with geom/->radians if needed." "The angles A and B must be the angles opposite sides a and b respectively; order matters." "Both angles must be in the range (0, π) and their sum must be less than π for a valid triangle; no validation." "If angles are very small or close to π, numerical instability can occur (sin of very small angle is also very small).")
  :drawbacks ("For two sides and an included angle, use geom/law-of-cosines-side instead (more stable)." "The law of sines can produce an ambiguous case (two possible triangles) when given one side and two angles; this verb returns only one." "For right triangles, geom/solve-right is faster and less prone to rounding error.")
  :usecases ("Solving triangles in ASA (Angle-Side-Angle) or AAS (Angle-Angle-Side) configurations." "Triangulation in surveying or navigation when two bearings and one baseline are known." "Computing the third side of a triangle when you know one side and two angles." "Graphics or physics: resolving a force or vector given direction constraints.")
  :related ("geom/law-of-cosines-side" "geom/law-of-cosines-angle" "geom/solve-right" "geom/->radians" "geom/triangle-area" "geom/distance")
  :learn (:concept "The law of sines and how it relates all sides and angles in a triangle; understanding when to apply it versus the law of cosines." :prerequisites ("Understanding the law of sines formula: a/sin(A) = b/sin(B)" "Familiarity with radians and the sin function" "Triangle classification (ASA, AAS, SSS, SAS, SSA)") :progression "Master this, then learn geom/law-of-cosines-side for SAS (Side-Angle-Side) triangles, and understand the ambiguous case (SSA).")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "An operator knows one side and the two angles adjacent to it in a triangulation; they need another side." :program "(define (asa-side a A B)
  (geom/law-of-sines-side a A B))
(asa-side 10 (/ math/pi 6) (/ math/pi 3))" :explanation "Given side a opposite angle A and another angle B, apply b = a·sin(B)/sin(A)." :meta "geom/law-of-sines-side is the correct verb because the input is ASA (angle-side-angle). Law of cosines would require the included side, which we don't have.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: sine-ratio recovery."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/law-of-sines-side 10 (/ math/pi 6) (/ math/pi 3))")
       (:domain "surveying (a metaphor domain — one baseline and two bearings triangulate the target)" :code "(define (survey base b1 b2) (list base b1 b2))")
       (:domain "math — sine rule a/sin A = b/sin B" :code "(define (sine-rule a A B) (list a A B))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung recovers a matching side using the ratio of sines to angles."
     :meta "The shape transfers because sine rule holds in any triangle.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "If A = B then the returned side equals a." :program "(define t (/ math/pi 4))
(< (abs (- (geom/law-of-sines-side 10 t t) 10)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ a > 0, θ ∈ (0, π). law-of-sines-side(a, θ, θ) = a" :meta "Isoceles-symmetry special case. If broken, the ratio order is wrong. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain law-of-sines-side to walk out all three sides of a triangle." :composition "(define (asa a A B)
  (let* ((C (- math/pi A B))
         (b (geom/law-of-sines-side a A B))
         (c (geom/law-of-sines-side a A C)))
    (list a b c)))
(asa 10 (/ math/pi 6) (/ math/pi 3))" :emergent "chain-solver: one measurement expands into three via repeated ratio calls." :meta "Belongs to the family of iterated-recovery patterns. See book-of-composition ch 14.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/midpoint"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(geom/midpoint x1 y1 x2 y2) -> (list x y)"
  :summary "Midpoint of a line segment between two points."
  :explanation "Returns the point exactly halfway between (x1, y1) and (x2, y2). The formula is ((x1 + x2) / 2, (y1 + y2) / 2). This is one of the simplest geometric operations and is used in bisection, centering, and symmetric constructions."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/midpoint 0 0 10 10)" :note "Returns (5 5), the center point between (0, 0) and (10, 10).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (bisect-segment seg)\n  (let ((p1 (car seg))\n        (p2 (cdr seg)))\n    (geom/midpoint (car p1) (cdr p1) (car p2) (cdr p2))))" :note "Helper that extracts endpoints from a segment representation and returns the midpoint.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (recursive-midpoint-refine depth p1 p2)\n  ;; Recursively subdivide a segment, returning all subdivision points\n  (if (= depth 0)\n      (list p1 p2)\n      (let ((mid (geom/midpoint (car p1) (cdr p1) (car p2) (cdr p2))))\n        (append (recursive-midpoint-refine (- depth 1) p1 mid)\n                (recursive-midpoint-refine (- depth 1) mid p2)))))" :note "Recursively bisects a segment to depth levels, generating intermediate points for smooth interpolation.")
  )
  :caveats ("Result is a list (x y), not a pair or point object." "Floating-point rounding can occur when coordinates are odd; use tolerance for comparisons." "No bounds checking; extreme coordinates compute without error.")
  :drawbacks ("For many intermediate points along a segment, use linear interpolation or spline curves instead of repeated bisection." "If you need the distance to the midpoint, compute separately; geom/midpoint does not return distance.")
  :usecases ("Finding the center of a line segment for layout or symmetry." "Bisecting intervals in numerical methods (e.g., binary search on a 2D space)." "Creating midpoints for Bézier curve control or spline interpolation." "Centering UI elements or sprites on a line.")
  :related ("geom/distance" "geom/triangle-area" "curve/bezier" "curve/hermite")
  :learn (:concept "The arithmetic mean in two dimensions; averaging coordinates as the fundamental operation for centeredness and balance." :prerequisites ("Understanding coordinate pairs (x, y)" "Basic arithmetic (addition, division by 2)") :progression "After mastering this, learn geom/distance to measure between points, and curve/bezier to interpolate smoothly between points.")
  :row-2-audit (
