(verb
  :name "geom/perimeter"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/perimeter p1 p2 p3) -> number"
  :summary "Sum of the three side lengths of a triangle."
  :explanation "Perimeter is the total distance around a closed polygon. For a triangle, it is the sum of all three side lengths. This verb expects three points and computes √((x₁−x₂)² + (y₁−y₂)²) for each pair, then adds them. It is useful for measuring the boundary of a triangular region or validating triangle proportions."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define triangle-pts (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 3 0) (geom/point 0 4)))\n(geom/perimeter (car triangle-pts) (cadr triangle-pts) (caddr triangle-pts))" :note "A 3–4–5 right triangle has perimeter 12.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define p1 (geom/point 0 0))\n(define p2 (geom/point 1 1))\n(define p3 (geom/point 1 0))\n(define perim (geom/perimeter p1 p2 p3))\n(define is-small? (< perim 5))" :note "Check whether a triangle's perimeter falls below a threshold for filtering or clustering.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (triangle-constraints pts-list)\n  (map (lambda (tri) (geom/perimeter (car tri) (cadr tri) (caddr tri))) pts-list))\n(define triangles (list (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 5 0) (geom/point 2.5 4))))\n(define perims (triangle-constraints triangles))\n(fold-left (lambda (acc p) (if (> p 10) (+ acc 1) acc)) 0 perims)" :note "Count how many triangles in a collection exceed a perimeter bound; composable with fold for batch geometry queries.")
  )
  :caveats ("Expects exactly three point objects; behavior is undefined for non-point inputs." "Computed distance assumes Euclidean metric (straight-line, not geodetic)." "Result is a device float; comparison should allow for small rounding errors.")
  :drawbacks ("Only works for triangles; use geom/polygon-perimeter for polygons with more than three vertices." "No validation that the three points actually form a non-degenerate triangle." "Recomputes distances each call; cache result if used repeatedly in tight loops.")
  :usecases ("Validating triangle proportions in a geometric constraint system." "Filtering triangles by size or complexity." "Computing total boundary length for rendering or physics simulation.")
  :related ("geom/polygon-perimeter" "geom/distance" "geom/triangle-area" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse")
  :learn (:concept "Perimeter as the sum of distances; understanding point-to-point measurement." :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/distance") :progression "Next learn geom/polygon-perimeter to generalize to arbitrary polygons, then geom/triangle-area to measure interior rather than boundary.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A fencing quote needs the total perimeter of a triangular plot given its three vertices." :program "(define (fence-length p1 p2 p3)
  (geom/perimeter p1 p2 p3))
(fence-length '(0 0) '(4 0) '(0 3))" :explanation "Sum the three edge distances." :meta "geom/perimeter is the correct verb for a triangle. For polygons of higher order use geom/polygon-perimeter.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: sum of edge measurements."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/perimeter '(0 0) '(3 0) '(0 4))")
       (:domain "running lap (a metaphor domain — total distance around a track)" :code "(define (lap-total seg1 seg2 seg3) (+ seg1 seg2 seg3))")
       (:domain "math — boundary integral of a polygonal region" :code "(define (boundary xs) (apply + xs))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung sums edge lengths to a total."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'perimeter' is a sum over boundary segments.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Perimeter is invariant under permutation of the three vertices." :program "(define p1 '(0 0)) (define p2 '(3 0)) (define p3 '(0 4))
(< (abs (- (geom/perimeter p1 p2 p3) (geom/perimeter p2 p3 p1))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ p1 p2 p3. perimeter(p1,p2,p3) = perimeter(p2,p3,p1) = perimeter(p3,p1,p2)" :meta "Cyclic invariance of the sum. If broken, one edge is being counted twice. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain perimeter with a linear cost model for a fencing quote." :composition "(define (quote-fence p1 p2 p3 cost-per-m)
  (* (geom/perimeter p1 p2 p3) cost-per-m))
(quote-fence '(0 0) '(4 0) '(0 3) 25)" :emergent "cost-model: geometric measurement × per-unit cost → total cost." :meta "Belongs to the family of measurement-to-cost pipelines. See book-of-composition ch 10.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/point"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/point x y) -> point"
  :summary "Construct a point at Cartesian coordinates (x, y)."
  :explanation "A point is the foundational geometric object: a location in 2D space. This verb packages two numbers into a point value that other geometry verbs expect. It uses bitwise encoding for efficiency. Think of a point as a tagged pair that carries Cartesian coordinates; all other plane geometry (distance, segments, polygons) is built from points."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define origin (geom/point 0 0))\n(define unit-x (geom/point 1 0))\n(define unit-y (geom/point 0 1))" :note "Three basic reference points: origin and the unit axes.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define vertices (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 2 1) (geom/point 1 3)))\n(define dist-01 (geom/distance (car vertices) (cadr vertices)))\n(display dist-01)" :note "Build a list of points and compute distance between the first two.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (random-points n)\n  (let loop ((i 0) (acc '()))\n    (if (= i n) (reverse acc)\n      (loop (+ i 1) (cons (geom/point (random) (random)) acc)))))\n(define pts (random-points 5))\n(define centroid-x (/ (fold-left (lambda (s p) (+ s (car p))) 0 pts) 5))\n(display centroid-x)" :note "Generate a random point cloud and compute the x-coordinate of the centroid; points integrate naturally with higher-order functions.")
  )
  :caveats ("Coordinates are device floats; very large or very small values may lose precision." "Point values are opaque; do not attempt to inspect or destructure them directly—use geom verbs to query properties." "The bitwise encoding is implementation-specific; two points equal in coordinates are bitwise equal, but direct bit manipulation is undefined behavior.")
  :drawbacks ("No built-in validation that coordinates are finite; NaN or infinity may propagate silently." "Points are 2D only; use vec/* for 3D or higher-dimensional vectors if needed." "Immutable; create a new point rather than modifying coordinates.")
  :usecases ("Defining vertices of triangles, polygons, and other planar shapes." "Serving as anchor points for rotations, reflections, and translations." "Marking positions in a grid, sprite, or scene for collision or rendering.")
  :related ("geom/distance" "geom/segment" "geom/triangle" "geom/circle" "geom/midpoint")
  :learn (:concept "Points as the atomic unit of plane geometry; Cartesian coordinates." :prerequisites () :progression "After mastering point construction, learn geom/distance (point-to-point measurement), then geom/segment and geom/triangle to build composite shapes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The operator wants to represent the origin of a coordinate system as a named value that other verbs can accept." :program "(define origin (geom/point 0 0))
origin" :explanation "Bind the origin to a name so subsequent code refers to it by intent, not by coordinates." :meta "geom/point is the correct verb because it produces the canonical point value. Two coordinates in a bare list would work in many geom calls but couldn't participate in point-typed dispatch.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: constructor — an atomic value assembled from primitives."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/point 3 4)")
       (:domain "mailing address (a metaphor domain — street and number bundle into an address value)" :code "(define (addr street number) (list 'addr street number))")
       (:domain "math — element of ℝ²" :code "(define (r2 x y) (list x y))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung packages a small tuple as a first-class value."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'assemble a compound from parts' is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Two points at the same coordinates are equal." :program "(equal? (geom/point 3 4) (geom/point 3 4))" :invariant "∀ x y. equal?(point(x,y), point(x,y))" :meta "Referential transparency of the constructor. If broken, the constructor is inserting nondeterminism (e.g., an identity tag). See book-of-math ch 6.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain point with a distance predicate." :composition "(define (near? a b)
  (< (geom/distance (car a) (cadr a) (car b) (cadr b)) 5))
(near? (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 3 4))" :emergent "typed-tuple + query: constructor and consumer form a small type discipline." :meta "Belongs to the family of value-plus-query patterns. See book-of-composition ch 8.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/polygon-area"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/polygon-area pts) -> number"
  :summary "Area of a polygon given a list of vertices, using the shoelace formula."
  :explanation "The shoelace formula (or Gauss's area formula) computes the signed area of any polygon from its vertex coordinates. Given a list of points in order (clockwise or counterclockwise), it returns the unsigned area. This is faster than triangulation and works for concave as well as convex polygons. Mental model: imagine the polygon's edges tracing a closed path; the formula sums cross-products to capture the enclosed region."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define square (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 1 0) (geom/point 1 1) (geom/point 0 1)))\n(geom/polygon-area square)" :note "A unit square has area 1.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define hexagon (list (geom/point 1 0) (geom/point 0.5 0.866) (geom/point -0.5 0.866) (geom/point -1 0) (geom/point -0.5 -0.866) (geom/point 0.5 -0.866)))\n(define hex-area (geom/polygon-area hexagon))\n(display (> hex-area 2.5))" :note "A regular hexagon with unit circumradius; shoelace formula handles arbitrary convex polygons.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (filter pred xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc '()))\n    (cond ((null? xs) (reverse acc))\n          ((pred (car xs)) (loop (cdr xs) (cons (car xs) acc)))\n          (else (loop (cdr xs) acc)))))\n(define (polygon-filter-by-area min-area pts-list)\n  (filter (lambda (poly) (> (geom/polygon-area poly) min-area)) pts-list))\n(define shapes (list\n  (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 2 0) (geom/point 2 2) (geom/point 0 2))\n  (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 0.5 0) (geom/point 0.5 0.5) (geom/point 0 0.5))))\n(polygon-filter-by-area 1 shapes)" :note "Filter a collection of polygons by minimum area; composable with higher-order verbs.")
  )
  :caveats ("Vertices must be in order (either clockwise or counterclockwise) for correct results; out-of-order points produce wrong areas." "Self-intersecting (non-simple) polygons may give unexpected results; the formula assumes a simple polygon." "An empty or single-point list is undefined behavior; always ensure at least three vertices.")
  :drawbacks ("Only works for 2D polygons; use geom/prism-volume for 3D solids." "Does not validate polygon simplicity or vertex ordering; garbage input produces garbage output without error." "Slower than precomputed bounding-box area for quick inclusion tests; use bounding boxes as a fast filter first.")
  :usecases ("Computing the size of an irregular boundary (map, level, region)." "Filtering shapes by minimum or maximum area in a geometry query." "Verifying that a polygon has the expected footprint during design or layout.")
  :related ("geom/polygon-perimeter" "geom/triangle-area" "geom/regular-polygon-area" "geom/point")
  :learn (:concept "The shoelace formula as a general polygon-area method; vertex ordering and simple polygons." :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/triangle-area") :progression "Learn geom/polygon-perimeter next to compute boundary length; then explore geom/regular-polygon-area and geom/regular-polygon-vertices for symmetric shapes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A land agent has surveyed the corners of an irregular parcel; they need its area." :program "(define (parcel-area pts) (geom/polygon-area pts))
(parcel-area (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 4 0) (geom/point 4 3) (geom/point 0 3)))" :explanation "Pass the ordered vertex list to the shoelace formula." :meta "geom/polygon-area is the correct verb because the shoelace formula handles convex and concave polygons in one shot. Triangulating and summing works but is more code.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: sum over signed slabs — area is a signed integral over polygon edges."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/polygon-area '((0 0) (4 0) (4 3) (0 3)))")
       (:domain "bookkeeping (a metaphor domain — total balance from a series of signed transactions)" :code "(define (balance xs) (apply + xs))")
       (:domain "math — line integral ∮(x dy − y dx) / 2" :code "(define (shoelace xs) (list 'signed-sum xs))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung adds signed contributions to reach a total."
     :meta "The shape transfers because signed-summation is the substrate of any 'net' measurement.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Reversing the vertex order negates the signed area (the impl takes absolute value, so magnitude is unchanged)." :program "(define pts '((0 0) (4 0) (4 3) (0 3)))
(< (abs (- (geom/polygon-area pts) (geom/polygon-area (reverse pts)))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ ordered pts. polygon-area(pts) = polygon-area(reverse(pts))" :meta "Orientation-invariant magnitude. If broken, sign leakage is polluting the return. See book-of-math ch 4 (shoelace formula).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain polygon-area with a filter to keep only large parcels." :composition "(define (large-parcels parcels min-area)
  (filter (lambda (p) (> (geom/polygon-area p) min-area)) parcels))
(large-parcels (list '((0 0) (10 0) (10 10) (0 10))) 50)" :emergent "filter-by-measurement: shapes are gated by a scalar predicate." :meta "Belongs to the family of measurement-gated filters. See book-of-composition ch 7.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/polygon-perimeter"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/polygon-perimeter pts) -> number"
  :summary "Sum of all side lengths of a polygon given an ordered list of vertices."
  :explanation "Perimeter extends from triangles to polygons of any number of sides. Given a list of points in order, it computes the distance between consecutive vertices (wrapping from the last back to the first) and sums them. Use this to measure the boundary length of any simple polygon—useful for proportions, scaling, and geometric constraints."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define square (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 1 0) (geom/point 1 1) (geom/point 0 1)))\n(geom/polygon-perimeter square)" :note "A unit square has perimeter 4.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define pentagon (list (geom/point 1 0) (geom/point 0.309 0.951) (geom/point -0.809 0.588) (geom/point -0.809 -0.588) (geom/point 0.309 -0.951)))\n(define perim (geom/polygon-perimeter pentagon))\n(define area (geom/polygon-area pentagon))\n(define isoperimetric (/ (* 4 3.14159) (* perim perim) area))" :note "Compute both perimeter and area; the isoperimetric ratio relates them for shape analysis.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (shape-summary pts)\n  (let ((p (geom/polygon-perimeter pts)) (a (geom/polygon-area pts)))\n    (list ':perimeter p ':area a ':aspect (/ p (sqrt a)))))\n(define rooms (list\n  (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 5 0) (geom/point 5 3) (geom/point 0 3))\n  (list (geom/point 10 10) (geom/point 12 10) (geom/point 12 11) (geom/point 10 11))))\n(map shape-summary rooms)" :note "Build a geometry summary record for each polygon, computing perimeter, area, and a derived aspect ratio.")
  )
  :caveats ("Vertices must be in order (connected by edges) for the result to be meaningful; random order produces incorrect perimeter." "Does not validate that the polygon is closed; if the last vertex is not intended to connect to the first, the result is still correct but conceptually odd." "Works for non-convex and concave polygons, but not for self-intersecting ones.")
  :drawbacks ("No validation that the list is non-empty; empty or single-point input causes undefined behavior." "Slower than precomputed or cached perimeter for repeated queries on the same polygon; memoize if querying many times." "Only 2D; for 3D polyhedra, sum face perimeters or use geom/pyramid-volume and geom/sphere-surface instead.")
  :usecases ("Measuring the boundary length of a map region, room, or obstacle." "Scaling a polygon proportionally based on perimeter constraints." "Analyzing shape compactness (perimeter-to-area ratio) for filtering or classification.")
  :related ("geom/polygon-area" "geom/distance" "geom/perimeter" "geom/regular-polygon-vertices")
  :learn (:concept "Perimeter as the sum of edge lengths; generalizing from triangle to arbitrary polygons." :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/distance" "geom/perimeter") :progression "Combine with geom/polygon-area to analyze shape properties; then explore geom/regular-polygon-area to compute areas of symmetric shapes more efficiently.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A fence quote for an irregular yard needs the boundary length given all corners." :program "(define (fence-yard pts) (geom/polygon-perimeter pts))
(fence-yard '((0 0) (4 0) (4 3) (0 3)))" :explanation "Sum the edge distances (last back to first)." :meta "geom/polygon-perimeter is the correct verb because it handles n-sided polygons. For triangles, geom/perimeter suffices, but this generalizes.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: sum over consecutive-pair measurements around a cycle."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/polygon-perimeter '((0 0) (4 0) (4 3) (0 3)))")
       (:domain "relay race (a metaphor domain — total time = sum of leg times, wrapping from last to first)" :code "(define (relay times) (apply + times))")
       (:domain "math — sum of edge weights around a Hamiltonian cycle" :code "(define (cycle-sum edges) (apply + edges))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung sums pairwise measurements around a closed loop."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'total around a cycle' is a general accumulation shape.")
