(verb
  :name "geom/prism-volume"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/prism-volume base-area height) -> number"
  :summary "Volume of a prism given the area of its base and its height."
  :explanation "A prism is a 3D solid with a uniform cross-section: imagine extruding a 2D shape straight upward. Its volume is simply base area × height. This formula applies to any prism (triangular, rectangular, pentagonal, etc.) as long as you know the base area. It is one of the simplest and most useful 3D formulas, especially for composite shapes made of multiple prisms."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define base-area 6)\n(define height 10)\n(geom/prism-volume base-area height)" :note "A prism with base area 6 and height 10 has volume 60.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define triangle-base (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 4 0) (geom/point 2 3)))\n(define tri-area (geom/triangle-area (car triangle-base) (cadr triangle-base) (caddr triangle-base)))\n(define prism-h 5)\n(define vol (geom/prism-volume tri-area prism-h))" :note "Compute the area of a triangular base, then use it to find the volume of a triangular prism.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (container-volume base-polygon height)\n  (let ((area (geom/polygon-area base-polygon)))\n    (geom/prism-volume area height)))\n(define tank-base (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 3 0) (geom/point 3 2) (geom/point 0 2)))\n(define tank-height 4)\n(define capacity (container-volume tank-base tank-height))\n(display (> capacity 20))" :note "Design a container by defining its base polygon and height, then compute capacity in a reusable function.")
  )
  :caveats ("Assumes the base is perpendicular to the height; oblique prisms require a different formula." "Base area must be correctly computed (using geom/polygon-area, geom/triangle-area, etc.); garbage input → garbage volume." "Height must be non-negative; negative height is mathematically valid but semantically odd.")
  :drawbacks ("Works only for prisms (uniform cross-section); for pyramids, use geom/pyramid-volume; for cylinders, use geom/cylinder-volume." "Does not validate that base-area and height are positive; no error checking." "Very simple formula; only useful in conjunction with base-area computation (which is the real work).")
  :usecases ("Computing the volume of a storage container or tank with a polygonal base." "Estimating material quantity (e.g., concrete) for a uniform extrusion." "Designing a level or room with a fixed footprint and variable height.")
  :related ("geom/polygon-area" "geom/cylinder-volume" "geom/cone-volume" "geom/pyramid-volume" "geom/triangle-area")
  :learn (:concept "Volume as area × height for prisms; scaling from 2D to 3D." :prerequisites ("geom/polygon-area" "geom/triangle-area") :progression "Learn geom/cylinder-volume (base area of a circle) and geom/pyramid-volume (1/3 × base area × height) to handle other common 3D shapes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A concrete estimator needs the volume of a prism-shaped foundation of known base area and height." :program "(define (concrete-vol base-area height) (geom/prism-volume base-area height))
(concrete-vol 20 0.3)" :explanation "Direct product. The result gives cubic meters." :meta "geom/prism-volume is the correct verb because it works for any base shape — you supply the base area yourself, so the same verb handles triangular, square, or hexagonal prisms.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
