(verb
  :name "geom/pyramid-volume"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/pyramid-volume base-area height) -> number"
  :summary "Volume of a pyramid given the area of its base and its height."
  :explanation "A pyramid tapers from a base (any polygon) to a point (apex). Unlike a prism (which has constant cross-section), a pyramid's cross-section shrinks linearly to zero at the apex. The volume formula is 1/3 × base area × height. The factor of 1/3 comes from calculus: if you stack three pyramids with the same base and height, they exactly fill a prism, so each pyramid is one-third of that volume."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define base-area 12)\n(define height 9)\n(geom/pyramid-volume base-area height)" :note "A pyramid with base area 12 and height 9 has volume 36 (one-third of 12 × 9).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define square-base (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 2 0) (geom/point 2 2) (geom/point 0 2)))\n(define sq-area (geom/polygon-area square-base))\n(define pyr-height 3)\n(define pyr-vol (geom/pyramid-volume sq-area pyr-height))\n(define prism-vol (geom/prism-volume sq-area pyr-height))\n(display (= pyr-vol (/ prism-vol 3)))" :note "Verify the 1/3 relationship: a pyramid with the same base and height as a prism has exactly one-third the volume.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (solid-of-revolution base-area height base-polygon)\n  (let ((mid-area (* base-area 0.5)) (pyr-vol (geom/pyramid-volume base-area height)))\n    (list ':pyramid-volume pyr-vol ':prism-volume (geom/prism-volume base-area height) ':ratio (/ pyr-vol (geom/prism-volume base-area height)))))\n(define my-base (list (geom/point 0 0) (geom/point 4 0) (geom/point 4 3) (geom/point 0 3)))\n(define base-a (geom/polygon-area my-base))\n(solid-of-revolution base-a 6 my-base)" :note "Compare pyramid and prism volumes for the same base and height; useful in structural or packing analysis.")
  )
  :caveats ("Assumes the apex is directly above the centroid of the base (a right pyramid); oblique pyramids with the apex offset require calculus." "Base area must be computed correctly; an incorrect base area propagates directly into the volume." "Height is measured from the base to the apex; do not confuse with slant height (which is different).")
  :drawbacks ("Formula only applies to pyramids with a single apex point; for truncated pyramids (frustums), use calculus or approximate." "No validation of inputs; negative height or area produces mathematically coherent but semantically wrong results." "Works in 3D only; there is no 2D analog.")
  :usecases ("Computing the volume of a tent, cone, or pyramidal structure." "Estimating fill material for a pyramid-shaped container." "Comparing storage efficiency: pyramids hold 1/3 the volume of a prism with the same base and height.")
  :related ("geom/prism-volume" "geom/polygon-area" "geom/cone-volume" "geom/sphere-volume")
  :learn (:concept "The 1/3 factor in pyramid volume; how solid shape determines volume scaling." :prerequisites ("geom/polygon-area" "geom/prism-volume") :progression "After pyramids, learn geom/cone-volume (pyramid with a circular base) and geom/sphere-volume to round out the common 3D shapes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A gravel pile shaped like a pyramid on a square base needs its volume estimated." :program "(define (pile base-area height) (geom/pyramid-volume base-area height))
(pile 25 6)" :explanation "Apply the 1/3 formula." :meta "geom/pyramid-volume is the correct verb because it captures the 1/3-of-prism ratio directly. Multiplying prism-volume by 1/3 works, but this verb names the intent.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: one-third of a bounding prism."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/pyramid-volume 25 6)")
       (:domain "pizza box (a metaphor domain — three pyramid volumes fit exactly in one box)" :code "(define (three-slots per-slot) (* 3 per-slot))")
       (:domain "math — volume of a solid tapering to a point" :code "(define (taper base h) (* base h 1/3))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung applies the 1/3 relationship of a tapered solid."
     :meta "The shape transfers because pyramidal integration always gives 1/3 the enclosing prism.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Pyramid volume equals one-third of the corresponding prism volume." :program "(define b 25) (define h 6)
(< (abs (- (geom/pyramid-volume b h) (/ (geom/prism-volume b h) 3))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ b > 0, h > 0. pyramid-volume(b,h) = prism-volume(b,h) / 3" :meta "The 1/3 identity for tapered solids. If broken, the coefficient drifted. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Compare pyramid to prism for a storage decision." :composition "(define (pack-choice base h)
  (list 'pyramid (geom/pyramid-volume base h)
        'prism   (geom/prism-volume base h)))
(pack-choice 20 5)" :emergent "measurement-bundle: two shapes compared side-by-side." :meta "Belongs to the family of comparative-measurement bundles. See book-of-composition ch 12.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse a b) -> number"
  :summary "Hypotenuse of a right triangle given the lengths of its two legs."
  :explanation "The Pythagorean theorem states that in a right triangle with legs a and b, the hypotenuse c satisfies c² = a² + b². This verb computes c = √(a² + b²). It is one of the most fundamental formulas in geometry and appears everywhere: distance calculations, physics, signal processing, and more. Mentally: the hypotenuse is the longest side, always opposite the right angle."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse 3 4)" :note "The classic 3–4–5 right triangle: hypotenuse is 5.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define p1 (geom/point 0 0))\n(define p2 (geom/point 3 4))\n(define distance-direct (geom/distance p1 p2))\n(define distance-pythag (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse 3 4))\n(display (= distance-direct distance-pythag))" :note "Distance between two points is equivalent to the hypotenuse of a right triangle with legs equal to Δx and Δy.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define cx (lambda args (list \"cx\" args)))\n(define cy (lambda args (list \"cy\" args)))\n(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (nearest-corner origin corners)\n  (let ((ox (car origin)) (oy (cadr origin)))\n    (fold-left (lambda (best corner)\n      (let ((cx (car corner)) (cy (cadr corner))\n            (dist (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse (- cx ox) (- cy oy))))\n        (if (< dist (caddr best)) (list cx cy dist) best)))\n      (list (car (car corners)) (cadr (car corners)) 999999)\n      (cdr corners))))\n(define origin '(0 0))\n(define corners '((3 4) (1 1) (5 5)))\n(nearest-corner origin corners)" :note "Find the nearest corner by computing Pythagorean distance to each; demonstrates composition with fold-left and closures.")
  )
  :caveats ("Computes distance only; does not return the angle or check that the triangle is actually right-angled." "Input order does not matter: pythagoras-hypotenuse(a, b) = pythagoras-hypotenuse(b, a)." "Both legs must be non-negative for meaningful results; negative legs produce positive hypotenuse (since they are squared).")
  :drawbacks ("Slower than precomputed or cached distance for repeated queries; if calling many times, memoize." "Very simple; the complexity is usually in setting up the legs, not in computing the hypotenuse." "Does not apply to non-right triangles; use geom/law-of-cosines-side instead.")
  :usecases ("Computing Euclidean distance in 2D (via Δx and Δy)." "Finding the diagonal of a rectangle or the distance across a grid." "Physics: velocity, displacement, or force magnitude from component values.")
  :related ("geom/pythagoras-leg" "geom/distance" "geom/triangle-area" "geom/right-triangle-angle")
  :learn (:concept "The Pythagorean theorem as a bridge between 1D legs and 2D distance; square-root as the inverse of squaring." :prerequisites ("math/pow" "geom/point") :progression "Learn geom/pythagoras-leg (solving for a missing leg), then geom/right-triangle-angle to find angles in right triangles.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A carpenter needs the diagonal of a rectangle of width 3 and height 4." :program "(define (diag w h) (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse w h))
(diag 3 4)" :explanation "Apply √(a² + b²) to the two legs." :meta "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse is the correct verb because it names the theorem directly. Using sqrt(a·a + b·b) works but is more error-prone (typos in exponents).")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: Euclidean norm of a two-component vector."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse 3 4)")
       (:domain "packing a box (a metaphor domain — box diagonal from width and height)" :code "(define (box-diag w h) (list 'diag w h))")
       (:domain "math — L² norm on ℝ²" :code "(define (l2 a b) (sqrt (+ (* a a) (* b b))))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung computes a scalar magnitude from two orthogonal components."
     :meta "The shape transfers because the L² norm is defined the same way in every inner-product space.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "The hypotenuse is symmetric in its two legs." :program "(< (abs (- (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse 3 4) (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse 4 3))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ a b. hypotenuse(a, b) = hypotenuse(b, a)" :meta "Argument-order symmetry of the L² norm. If broken, one squaring is missing. See book-of-math ch 4 (Pythagorean theorem).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain hypotenuse to compute a full 2D magnitude." :composition "(define (speed vx vy) (geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse vx vy))
(speed 3 4)" :emergent "vector-to-magnitude: component pair reduces to a scalar." :meta "Belongs to the family of vector-magnitude patterns: same family as velocity → speed, force → force-magnitude. See book-of-composition ch 10.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/pythagoras-leg"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/pythagoras-leg hypotenuse known-leg) -> number"
  :summary "Length of the unknown leg of a right triangle given the hypotenuse and one leg."
  :explanation "The inverse of the Pythagorean theorem: if c² = a² + b² and you know c (hypotenuse) and a (one leg), you can solve for b. Rearranging, b = √(c² − a²). This is useful when you know the diagonal (or maximum extent) and one dimension, and need to find the other. Mentally: the unknown leg is always shorter than the hypotenuse."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/pythagoras-leg 5 3)" :note "Given hypotenuse 5 and one leg 3, the other leg is 4 (the 3–4–5 triangle).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define diagonal 10)\n(define width 6)\n(define height (geom/pythagoras-leg diagonal width))\n(display (list ':width width ':height height ':diagonal diagonal))" :note "Computing the height of a rectangle given its diagonal and width.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (filter pred xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc '()))\n    (cond ((null? xs) (reverse acc))\n          ((pred (car xs)) (loop (cdr xs) (cons (car xs) acc)))\n          (else (loop (cdr xs) acc)))))\n(define (rect-from-diagonal-and-side diag side)\n  (let ((other (geom/pythagoras-leg diag side)))\n    (list ':width side ':height other ':area (* side other) ':perimeter (* 2 (+ side other)))))\n(define aspect-ratios (map (lambda (w) (rect-from-diagonal-and-side 13 w)) (list 5 12 8)))\n(filter (lambda (r) (> (list-ref r 3) 50)) aspect-ratios)" :note "Generate rectangles with a fixed diagonal but varying width; filter by area. Demonstrates composition with map and filter.")
  )
  :caveats ("Assumes hypotenuse ≥ known-leg; if known-leg > hypotenuse, the result is NaN (square root of a negative number)." "Does not check that the triangle is a right triangle; assumes the inputs are semantically valid." "Result is a device float subject to rounding error; exact comparison with another computed value may fail.")
  :drawbacks ("Only works for right triangles; for general triangles, use geom/law-of-cosines-side with angle information." "No error handling for invalid inputs (e.g., negative hypotenuse or known-leg); caller must validate." "Does not distinguish which leg is unknown; both legs play the same role in the formula.")
  :usecases ("Deriving a missing dimension when diagonal and one side are known (e.g., screen aspect ratio)." "Computing clearance or reach in a constrained space." "Game design: finding the height of a jump given maximum horizontal distance and platform width.")
  :related ("geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse" "geom/distance" "geom/right-triangle-angle" "geom/triangle-area")
  :learn (:concept "Inverting the Pythagorean theorem; solving for a missing component." :prerequisites ("geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse" "math/pow") :progression "After learning both pythagoras verbs, explore geom/right-triangle-angle to compute angles; then geom/law-of-cosines-side for non-right triangles.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A ladder of length 10 leans against a wall with its base 6 units out; the operator needs its reach height." :program "(define (ladder-reach hyp base) (geom/pythagoras-leg hyp base))
(ladder-reach 10 6)" :explanation "Apply √(hyp² − base²)." :meta "geom/pythagoras-leg is the correct verb because it inverts the theorem. Computing sqrt(hyp·hyp − known·known) works but the named verb clarifies which leg is unknown.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: complementary-magnitude recovery — knowing the hypotenuse and one leg gives the other."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/pythagoras-leg 5 3)")
       (:domain "budget split (a metaphor domain — total minus known share = the other share)" :code "(define (other-share total known) (- total known))")
       (:domain "math — Pythagorean identity solved for the missing leg" :code "(define (leg h k) (sqrt (- (* h h) (* k k))))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung recovers a missing component from a total and a known component."
     :meta "The shape transfers because the norm identity constrains any two components to determine the third.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applying pythagoras-hypotenuse to the leg and known-leg reconstructs the hypotenuse." :program "(define h 5) (define a 3)
(define b (geom/pythagoras-leg h a))
