(verb
  :name "geom/reflect-line"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/reflect-line point a b c) -> point"
  :summary "Reflect a point across a line defined by the equation ax + by + c = 0."
  :explanation "Reflection across an arbitrary line is a fundamental isometry in the plane. Given a point and a line equation, this verb computes the mirror image of the point with respect to that line. The line is encoded as coefficients (a, b, c) where ax + by + c = 0. This is useful for symmetry operations, creating mirror-image geometry, and solving problems where you need the symmetric counterpart of a point relative to a dividing line."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/reflect-line (geom/point 1 0) 0 1 0)" :note "Reflect point (1, 0) across the line y = 0 (the x-axis); expect (1, 0) unchanged since it's on the axis.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(geom/reflect-line (geom/point 3 4) 1 0 0)" :note "Reflect (3, 4) across the vertical line x = 0; expect (-3, 4).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((pts (list (geom/point 0 1) (geom/point 1 0) (geom/point 2 3))))\n  (map (lambda (p) (geom/reflect-line p 1 1 0)) pts))" :note "Reflect a set of points across the line x + y = 0 (the anti-diagonal); map applies the reflection to each point in the list.")
  )
  :caveats ("The line equation ax + by + c = 0 must have a and b not both zero (otherwise the line is undefined)." "Floating-point precision may introduce small errors in the reflected coordinates." "The verb operates on individual points; for polygons, reflect each vertex separately using map or for-each.")
  :drawbacks ("More computationally expensive than axis-aligned reflections (geom/reflect-x, geom/reflect-y); prefer those when applicable." "Requires three coefficients instead of zero (for axis-aligned cases), adding notational overhead.")
  :usecases ("Creating symmetric artwork or game assets (mirror a sprite across a diagonal line)." "Solving geometry proofs involving reflection properties." "Simulating light reflection off a tilted surface.")
  :related ("geom/reflect-x" "geom/reflect-y" "geom/reflect-origin" "geom/rotate" "geom/transform-polygon")
  :learn (:concept "arbitrary-line reflection as a geometric isometry" :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/reflect-x" "geom/reflect-y") :progression "Learn the special cases (axis reflections) first, then understand the general line case; apply to transforming polygons with geom/transform-polygon.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A designer wants a mirror image of a logo across a diagonal reference line ax+by+c=0." :program "(define (mirror-pt pt a b c)
  (geom/reflect-line pt a b c))
(mirror-pt (geom/point 2 3) 1 -1 0)" :explanation "Apply the reflection formula. Result is the mirrored coordinate." :meta "geom/reflect-line is the correct verb for arbitrary-axis reflection. reflect-x/y only handle horizontal/vertical mirrors.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: isometry — a distance-preserving symmetry."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/reflect-line '(2 3) 1 0 0)")
       (:domain "printing (a metaphor domain — printing on the other side of a mirror)" :code "(define (mirror side) (list 'other-side side))")
       (:domain "math — orthogonal reflection across a hyperplane" :code "(define (reflect-hyp pt n) (list pt n))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung is a distance-preserving map fixing the reference set pointwise."
     :meta "The shape transfers because reflection is a universal isometry.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applying reflect-line twice across the same line returns the original point (involution)." :program "(define p (geom/point 2 3))
(define once (geom/reflect-line p 1 -1 0))
(define twice (geom/reflect-line once 1 -1 0))
(equal? p twice)" :invariant "∀ p, line ℓ. reflect-line(reflect-line(p, ℓ), ℓ) = p" :meta "Involution: order-2 group element. If broken, the impl is not exactly reflecting. See book-of-math ch 6 (isometries).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain reflect-line with a polygon map to mirror a whole shape." :composition "(define (mirror-shape pts a b c)
  (map (lambda (p) (geom/reflect-line p a b c)) pts))
(mirror-shape (list (geom/point 1 0) (geom/point 0 1)) 1 -1 0)" :emergent "polygon-transform: pointwise reflection lifts to shape-level." :meta "Belongs to the family of pointwise map-over-collection patterns. See book-of-composition ch 5.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/reflect-origin"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/reflect-origin point) -> point"
  :summary "Reflect a point through the origin (180° rotation about the origin)."
  :explanation "Reflection through the origin maps a point (x, y) to (-x, -y). This is equivalent to rotating 180° about the origin, but is often used semantically when describing point-symmetry or central symmetry. It is a special case of both rotation and reflection. Use this when you need to create a point-symmetric copy of a shape or find the antipodal point."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/reflect-origin (geom/point 3 4))" :note "Reflect (3, 4) through origin; expect (-3, -4).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(geom/reflect-origin (geom/point 0 5))" :note "Reflect (0, 5) through origin; expect (0, -5).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((vertices (list (geom/point 1 1) (geom/point -1 1) (geom/point 0 -1))))\n  (map geom/reflect-origin vertices))" :note "Create a point-symmetric copy of a triangle by reflecting all vertices through the origin.")
  )
  :caveats ("The origin itself maps to itself: (geom/reflect-origin (geom/point 0 0)) → (0, 0)." "This is not the same as reflection across a line (use geom/reflect-x, geom/reflect-y, or geom/reflect-line for those).")
  :drawbacks ("Limited use; often geom/rotate with angle π is more explicit about intent." "Only one degree of freedom (no parameters); cannot reflect through arbitrary centers.")
  :usecases ("Creating centrally-symmetric patterns or mandalas." "Generating the antipodal point on a tile or in game physics.")
  :related ("geom/reflect-x" "geom/reflect-y" "geom/reflect-line" "geom/rotate" "geom/rotate-about")
  :learn (:concept "central symmetry and point reflection" :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/reflect-x" "geom/reflect-y") :progression "Start with axis reflections; then learn that origin reflection is a special composition.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A designer wants a 180°-symmetric copy of a shape without doing a full rotation." :program "(define (antipode pt) (geom/reflect-origin pt))
(antipode (geom/point 3 4))" :explanation "Direct application. Point (3,4) → (-3,-4)." :meta "geom/reflect-origin is the correct verb because it names the intent 'reflect through the origin'. Using rotate by π radians gives the same result but is less clear.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: negation — every component is inverted through a fixed center."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/reflect-origin '(3 4))")
       (:domain "photo negatives (a metaphor domain — flip colors around gray = flip coordinates around zero)" :code "(define (negate x) (- x))")
       (:domain "math — additive inverse in a group" :code "(define (inverse x) (- x))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung inverts a value through a fixed reference."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'invert through zero' is universal in additive groups.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applying reflect-origin twice returns the original." :program "(define p (geom/point 3 4))
(equal? p (geom/reflect-origin (geom/reflect-origin p)))" :invariant "∀ p. reflect-origin(reflect-origin(p)) = p" :meta "Involution. If broken, one component is not being negated. See book-of-math ch 6.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain reflect-origin with a polygon map for a centrally-symmetric copy." :composition "(define (antipode-shape pts)
  (map geom/reflect-origin pts))
(antipode-shape (list '(1 1) '(-1 1) '(0 -1)))" :emergent "polygon-antipode: pointwise negation over a whole shape." :meta "Belongs to the family of pointwise-transform patterns. See book-of-composition ch 5.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/reflect-x"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/reflect-x point) -> point"
  :summary "Reflect a point across the x-axis."
  :explanation "Reflection across the x-axis is the simplest reflection: it flips the sign of the y-coordinate while leaving x unchanged. A point (x, y) becomes (x, -y). This is fundamental for creating vertical mirror images and is the building block for understanding more complex reflections."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/reflect-x (geom/point 2 3))" :note "Reflect (2, 3) across x-axis; expect (2, -3).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(geom/reflect-x (geom/point -1 5))" :note "Reflect (-1, 5) across x-axis; expect (-1, -5).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (flip-polygon pts)\n  (map geom/reflect-x pts))\n(flip-polygon (list (geom/point 0 2) (geom/point 1 1) (geom/point 2 2)))" :note "Define a helper to flip any polygon vertically by reflecting all vertices; useful for creating upside-down copies.")
  )
  :caveats ("Points on the x-axis (y = 0) map to themselves." "This only reflects vertically; use geom/reflect-y for horizontal reflection.")
  :drawbacks ("Very limited scope; only useful for vertical mirroring." "For arbitrary-axis reflection, use geom/reflect-line instead.")
  :usecases ("Flipping sprites or game graphics upside-down." "Creating symmetric patterns across the x-axis." "Solving problems involving symmetry about a horizontal line.")
  :related ("geom/reflect-y" "geom/reflect-origin" "geom/reflect-line" "geom/rotate" "geom/transform-polygon")
  :learn (:concept "axis-aligned reflection" :prerequisites ("geom/point") :progression "This is often the first reflection to learn; pair it with geom/reflect-y, then move to arbitrary lines with geom/reflect-line.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A game must mirror an enemy sprite's y-coordinate when it crosses the ground to bounce it." :program "(define (bounce-y pt) (geom/reflect-x pt))
(bounce-y '(3 5))" :explanation "Flip the sign of the y component." :meta "geom/reflect-x is the correct verb because it names the axis of reflection. Manually negating y is a two-line error surface.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: single-coordinate negation."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/reflect-x '(3 5))")
       (:domain "image editing (a metaphor domain — vertical flip in a graphics editor)" :code "(define (flip-v img) (list 'flipped-v img))")
       (:domain "math — action of the x-axis reflection element in O(2)" :code "(define (o2-x pt) (list (car pt) (- (cadr pt))))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung reflects across the x-axis by negating one component."
     :meta "The shape transfers because it's the same element of the symmetry group.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applying reflect-x twice yields the identity." :program "(define p '(3 5))
(equal? p (geom/reflect-x (geom/reflect-x p)))" :invariant "∀ p. reflect-x(reflect-x(p)) = p" :meta "Involution. If broken, sign is not exactly negated. See book-of-math ch 6.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain reflect-x on a whole shape to build a vertical-mirror pattern." :composition "(define (mirror-vert pts) (map geom/reflect-x pts))
(mirror-vert '((1 2) (3 4)))" :emergent "polygon-mirror: pointwise flip lifts to shape." :meta "Belongs to the family of shape-symmetry generators. See book-of-composition ch 5.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/reflect-y"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/reflect-y point) -> point"
  :summary "Reflect a point across the y-axis."
  :explanation "Reflection across the y-axis flips the sign of the x-coordinate while leaving y unchanged. A point (x, y) becomes (-x, y). This creates a horizontal mirror image and is the natural complement to geom/reflect-x. Together, these two form the basis for understanding multi-axis symmetry."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/reflect-y (geom/point 3 4))" :note "Reflect (3, 4) across y-axis; expect (-3, 4).")
