(verb
  :name "geom/right-triangle-angle"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/right-triangle-angle opposite hypotenuse) -> number"
  :summary "Compute an acute angle of a right triangle given opposite side and hypotenuse (inverse sine)."
  :explanation "In a right triangle, the sine of an acute angle is the ratio of the opposite side to the hypotenuse: sin(θ) = opposite / hypotenuse. This verb inverts that: given opposite and hypotenuse, it returns the angle θ in radians. This is essential for solving right triangles and converting between side lengths and angles."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/right-triangle-angle 1 2)" :note "Acute angle when opposite = 1 and hypotenuse = 2; expect arcsin(0.5) = π/6 ≈ 0.524 radians (30°).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(geom/right-triangle-angle 3 5)" :note "Acute angle in a 3-4-5 right triangle; expect arcsin(0.6) ≈ 0.6435 radians ≈ 36.87°.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((cases (list (list 1 2) (list 3 5) (list 7 25))))\n  (map (lambda (sides) (geom/right-triangle-angle (car sides) (cadr sides))) cases))" :note "Compute angles for several right triangles in batch; demonstrates mapping the verb over a list of (opposite, hypotenuse) pairs.")
  )
  :caveats ("opposite must be less than or equal to hypotenuse; otherwise the result is NaN or undefined." "Returns an angle in radians; use geom/->degrees to convert to degrees if needed." "The result is in the range [0, π/2] (0° to 90°).")
  :drawbacks ("Only computes one of the two acute angles; to find the other, subtract from π/2." "Numerically unstable if opposite / hypotenuse is very close to 1 (angle near 90°); use geom/arccos with adjacent / hypotenuse instead if needed.")
  :usecases ("Solving right triangles given side lengths." "Computing angles for navigation or aiming in games (e.g., converting distance and height to angle)." "Verifying geometric properties and relationships.")
  :related ("geom/arcsin" "geom/arccos" "geom/arctan" "geom/solve-right" "geom/->degrees" "geom/->radians")
  :learn (:concept "inverse trigonometric functions and right triangle solving" :prerequisites ("geom/sin" "geom/arcsin" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse") :progression "Learn sin, cos, tan; then learn their inverses (arcsin, arccos, arctan); use them to solve right triangles completely.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A ramp designer knows the ramp's rise and slant length; they need its angle above horizontal." :program "(define (ramp-angle rise slant)
  (geom/->degrees (geom/right-triangle-angle rise slant)))
(ramp-angle 3 5)" :explanation "Apply arcsin(opposite/hypotenuse), then convert to degrees for the report." :meta "geom/right-triangle-angle is the correct verb because it inverts the sine directly. arctan(rise/√(slant²−rise²)) is equivalent but more code.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: inverse-recovery from a ratio."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/right-triangle-angle 3 5)")
       (:domain "recipe (a metaphor domain — from measured cup ratios, deduce ingredient percentages)" :code "(define (ratio-to-pct r) (* r 100))")
       (:domain "math — arcsin as inverse-scalar recovery" :code "(define (arcsin-frac o h) (list 'ratio o h))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung takes two related magnitudes and recovers the angular relationship."
     :meta "The shape transfers because inverse-scalar recovery is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "The returned angle satisfies sin(θ)·hyp = opp." :program "(define theta (geom/right-triangle-angle 3 5))
(< (abs (- (* (sin theta) 5) 3)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ opp ≤ hyp. sin(right-triangle-angle(opp,hyp)) · hyp = opp" :meta "Consistency with the sine definition. If broken, the ratio is inverted. See book-of-math ch 5.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain right-triangle-angle with a physics loop for gravity-along-slope." :composition "(define (gravity-along rise slant g)
  (let ((theta (geom/right-triangle-angle rise slant)))
    (* g (sin theta))))
(gravity-along 3 5 9.81)" :emergent "geometry-into-physics: an angle feeds a force decomposition." :meta "Belongs to the family of adapter patterns between geometry and physics. See book-of-composition ch 11.")
