(verb
  :name "geom/rotate"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/rotate x y theta) -> (x' y')"
  :summary "Rotate the point (x, y) counterclockwise about the origin by theta radians; return the rotated coordinates."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "3-arg positional form: separate x, y, theta. Returns a 2-list (x', y'). Older docs promised a point-list first argument; the actual impl takes flat positional args. Compose with car/cadr of a point-list if you have one: (geom/rotate (car pt) (cadr pt) theta)."
  :explanation "Rotation about the origin: point (x, y) rotated by angle θ counterclockwise becomes (x cos θ - y sin θ, x sin θ + y cos θ). Angle is in radians."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/rotate 1 0 0)" :note "Zero rotation, no change. Returns (1 0).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "apprentice" :code "(geom/rotate 1 0 (geom/->radians 90))" :note "90 degrees counterclockwise. Returns (~0 1) — the unit x-axis rotated to the y-axis (tiny float epsilon for the near-zero x component).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(geom/rotate 3 4 (geom/->radians 180))" :note "180-degree rotation flips both coords. Returns (~-3 ~-4).")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (rotate-point-list pts theta)\n  (map (lambda (p) (geom/rotate (car p) (cadr p) theta)) pts))\n(rotate-point-list '((1 0) (0 1) (-1 0)) (geom/->radians 90))" :note "Adapter: given a point-list format, rotate each. Handy when working with polygon vertex lists rather than flat coords.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "master" :code "(define (rosette-vertices n)\n  ;; Generate n equally-spaced points on the unit circle by rotating (1,0)\n  ;; by k*(2*pi/n) for k = 0..n-1. Classic construction for regular polygons.\n  (let loop ((k 0) (acc '()))\n    (if (>= k n)\n        (reverse acc)\n        (let ((theta (/ (* 2 3.141592653589793 k) n)))\n          (loop (+ k 1)\n                (cons (geom/rotate 1 0 theta) acc))))))\n(length (rosette-vertices 8))" :note "Build an 8-vertex rosette (unit octagon). Returns 8 — the count of vertices. Extend to draw regular polygons by connecting them with geom/segment.")
  )
  :caveats ("theta is in radians, not degrees; use geom/->radians to convert." "Rotation is counterclockwise; negative angles rotate clockwise." "Floating-point precision may introduce small rounding errors, especially for non-special angles.")
  :drawbacks ("Always rotates about the origin; for rotation about an arbitrary point, use geom/rotate-about instead." "More expensive than no transformation; avoid rotating the same point multiple times in a loop (rotate once and reuse).")
  :usecases ("Rotating game sprites or obstacles to face a direction." "Implementing camera rotations." "Creating rotating animations or patterns." "Turning vehicles or characters to match their velocity.")
  :related ("geom/rotate-about" "geom/reflect-x" "geom/reflect-y" "geom/->radians" "geom/->degrees" "geom/sin" "geom/cos")
  :learn (:concept "rotation matrices and counterclockwise orientation" :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/sin" "geom/cos" "geom/->radians") :progression "Learn sin/cos first to understand rotation formulas; then apply geom/rotate to points and polygons; extend to geom/rotate-about for arbitrary centers.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A UI element must rotate 90° counterclockwise around the origin as an animation frame." :program "(define (rotate-frame x y)
  (geom/rotate x y (/ math/pi 2)))
(rotate-frame 1 0)" :explanation "Apply the rotation formula. (1,0) becomes ~(0,1)." :meta "geom/rotate is the correct verb because it uses the standard rotation matrix. Manually computing (cos θ x − sin θ y, sin θ x + cos θ y) is possible but a common source of sign errors.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: isometry — angle-preserving action of a group."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/rotate 1 0 (/ math/pi 2))")
       (:domain "turntable (a metaphor domain — record spins under the needle)" :code "(define (spin angle) (list 'spun angle))")
       (:domain "math — SO(2) action on ℝ²" :code "(define (so2 theta) (list theta))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung is an angle-preserving rotation of the plane."
     :meta "The shape transfers because rotation is a canonical isometry.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Rotating by 2π returns the original point." :program "(define p (geom/rotate 3 4 (* 2 math/pi)))
(and (< (abs (- (car p) 3)) 1e-9) (< (abs (- (cadr p) 4)) 1e-9))" :invariant "∀ x y. rotate(x, y, 2π) ≈ (x, y)" :meta "Periodicity 2π. If broken, the impl is not exactly using cos/sin. See book-of-math ch 6.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain rotate over a vertex list to spin a whole shape." :composition "(define (spin-shape pts theta)
  (map (lambda (p) (geom/rotate (car p) (cadr p) theta)) pts))
(spin-shape '((1 0) (0 1)) (/ math/pi 2))" :emergent "polygon-spinner: pointwise rotation lifts to shape." :meta "Belongs to the family of shape-transform patterns. See book-of-composition ch 5.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/rotate-about"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/rotate-about point center theta) -> point"
  :summary "Rotates a point around a center point by an angle in degrees."
  :explanation "Given a point, a center of rotation, and an angle in degrees, returns the new coordinates of the point after rotating it counterclockwise about the center. This is a pure transformation: the original point is unchanged. The angle is measured in degrees, not radians. Internally uses device-level trigonometry for speed."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/rotate-about (list 1 0) (list 0 0) 90)" :note "Rotates point (1,0) by 90° around origin; result is near (0,1)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((center (list 3 3))\n      (point (list 5 3)))\n  (geom/rotate-about point center 45))" :note "Rotates (5,3) about center (3,3) by 45°; returns point at the rotated distance")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((vertices (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 1 1) (list 0 1)))\n      (center (list 0.5 0.5)))\n  (map (lambda (v) (geom/rotate-about v center 45)) vertices))" :note "Rotates all four corners of a unit square 45° about its center; builds a diamond")
  )
  :caveats ("Angle is in degrees, not radians" "Returns a fresh point; does not mutate the input" "Rotation is counterclockwise; negative angles rotate clockwise" "Points and center must be 2-element lists [x y]")
  :drawbacks ("Not optimized for batch rotation of many points; consider pre-computing the rotation matrix for repeated use" "Device floating-point precision limits accuracy at extreme angles")
  :usecases ("Spinning a game sprite or entity around a pivot" "Rotating a polygon or shape during a canvas draw" "Building orbital mechanics or circular motion paths" "Transforming vertices of a shape in a graphics pipeline")
  :related ("geom/rotate" "geom/translate" "geom/reflect-origin" "geom/transform-polygon")
  :learn (:concept "2D rotation as a matrix transformation and the role of the center point as an anchor" :prerequisites ("geom/point" "geom/distance") :progression "After mastering rotation about a point, study geom/transform-polygon to rotate entire shapes, then move to curve/eval for rotations in parametric space")
