(verb
  :name "geom/sphere-surface"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/sphere-surface radius) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the surface area of a sphere given its radius."
  :explanation "The surface area of a sphere is 4πr². Given the radius, this returns the total area of the sphere's outer surface. This is a pure calculation with no side effects. Useful for paint coverage, heat dissipation, and material estimates."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/sphere-surface 1)" :note "Unit sphere; returns 4π ≈ 12.57")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(geom/sphere-surface 5)" :note "Sphere of radius 5; returns 100π ≈ 314.16")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((earth-radius-km 6371))\n  (geom/sphere-surface earth-radius-km))" :note "Earth's surface area in km²; returns ≈ 510 million km²")
  )
  :caveats ("Radius must be positive; zero or negative radius is valid mathematically but meaningless" "Returns a floating-point number; use exact/* for symbolic answers" "No validation of input type; passing a non-number may cause a silent error")
  :drawbacks ("Does not support ellipsoids (three unequal semi-axes); only spheres" "No built-in function for paint coverage or material cost; caller must multiply by density")
  :usecases ("Calculating paint or coating needed for a spherical tank" "Heat dissipation from a spherical object (surface area × emissivity)" "Estimating atmospheric load on a pressurized sphere" "Graphics: billboard sprite size for a distant spherical object")
  :related ("geom/sphere-volume" "geom/circle-area" "geom/cylinder-surface" "geom/cone-surface")
  :learn (:concept "How surface area scales with the square of radius (doubling radius quadruples surface); relationship between 2D circle area and 3D sphere surface area" :prerequisites ("const/pi" "geom/circle-area") :progression "Pair with geom/sphere-volume to compare surface-area-to-volume ratio; then move to calc/surface-integral for curved surfaces in calculus")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A paint shop must estimate paint for a spherical tank of given radius." :program "(define (paint-area r) (geom/sphere-surface r))
(paint-area 5)" :explanation "Apply 4πr²." :meta "geom/sphere-surface is the correct verb because it uses the closed 4πr² form. Integrating gives the same result but wastes cycles.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: quadratic surface scaling."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/sphere-surface 5)")
       (:domain "beach balls (a metaphor domain — bigger ball needs more material)" :code "(define (material size) (list 'sqm size))")
       (:domain "math — surface area homogeneous of degree 2 in radius" :code "(define (hom-2 r) (* r r))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung scales output as the square of a linear parameter."
     :meta "The shape transfers because surface area of any similar family scales quadratically.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Doubling radius quadruples surface area." :program "(define s1 (geom/sphere-surface 3))
(define s2 (geom/sphere-surface 6))
(< (abs (- s2 (* 4 s1))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ r > 0. sphere-surface(2r) = 4 · sphere-surface(r)" :meta "Homogeneous of degree 2. If broken, the exponent drifted. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
