(verb
  :name "geom/tan"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/tan angle-degrees) -> number"
  :summary "Tangent of an angle measured in degrees."
  :explanation "Returns the tangent (ratio of opposite to adjacent side) of the given angle. The angle is expressed in degrees (not radians), and the result is a device float. Useful when working with trigonometry in degree-based coordinate systems or when reasoning about slopes and angles in diagrams."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/tan 45)" :note "45° has tangent ≈ 1.0, so the result is close to 1")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define slope (geom/tan 30))\n(* slope 10)" :note "Compute rise-over-run for a 30° incline, then multiply by a distance to get height")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (ramp-rise angle base-length)\n  (* base-length (geom/tan angle)))\n(ramp-rise 20 100)" :note "Encapsulate angle-to-slope conversion in a reusable function; models physical ramp design")
  )
  :caveats ("Input is in degrees, not radians—do not pass radian values." "tan(90°) and tan(270°) are undefined (vertical asymptotes); results will be very large or ±infinity." "For angles near 90°, tan grows steeply; small angle changes produce large output swings.")
  :drawbacks ("If you need radians, convert first with (geom/->radians angle)." "For inverse tangent (angle from slope), use (geom/arctan slope) and convert back to degrees with (geom/->degrees)." "For right-triangle work with known sides, (geom/right-triangle-angle) may be clearer.")
  :usecases ("Finding the slope of a line given its angle of inclination." "Calculating height or distance in right-triangle geometry problems." "Reasoning about ramps, roofs, or any surface at a known angle." "Physics simulations where force components depend on an angle.")
  :related ("geom/sin" "geom/arctan" "geom/right-triangle-angle" "geom/->degrees" "geom/->radians" "geom/angle-between")
  :learn (:concept "Trigonometric function: tangent as a ratio in a right triangle." :prerequisites ("Basic understanding of degrees vs. radians" "Familiarity with right triangles (opposite, adjacent, hypotenuse)") :progression "After mastering geom/tan, learn geom/arctan to reverse the relationship, then explore geom/solve-right to solve full triangle problems.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "An operator has a slope angle in degrees and needs to translate it to a rise/run ratio." :program "(define (rise-per-run angle-deg) (geom/tan angle-deg))
(rise-per-run 30)" :explanation "Apply tan directly." :meta "geom/tan is the correct verb because Motoi convention is degrees. sin/cos ratio would work but is two calls.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: slope-from-angle map."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/tan 45)")
       (:domain "stair pitch (a metaphor domain — angle vs step ratio)" :code "(define (pitch angle-deg) (list angle-deg))")
       (:domain "math — tan as a periodic real function with vertical asymptotes" :code "(define (tan-def t) (list t))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung takes an angle and returns a slope."
     :meta "The shape transfers because slope-from-angle is a universal geometric operation.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "tan(45°) = 1." :program "(< (abs (- (geom/tan 45) 1)) 1e-9)" :invariant "tan(45°) = 1" :meta "Standard-angle anchor. If broken, the degree→radian conversion is wrong. See book-of-math ch 5.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
