(verb
  :name "geom/transform-polygon"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/transform-polygon points transform-fn ...args) -> list-of-points"
  :summary "Apply a geometric transformation (translate, rotate, reflect, dilate, etc.) to a polygon."
  :explanation "Takes a list of point coordinates and applies a single transformation function (specified by name and arguments) to each point in the polygon. The transformation function is one of geom/translate, geom/rotate, geom/reflect-x, geom/reflect-y, geom/reflect-origin, geom/reflect-line, geom/rotate-about, or geom/dilate. Returns a new list of transformed points, preserving the polygon's structure but altering its position, orientation, or scale."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/transform-polygon '((0 0) (1 0) (1 1)) 'geom/translate 2 3)" :note "Translate a triangle right by 2 and up by 3; all points shift by the same vector")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define square '((0 0) (1 0) (1 1) (0 1)))\n(geom/transform-polygon square 'geom/rotate 45)" :note "Rotate a square 45° counterclockwise around the origin")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (scale-from-center polygon scale-factor cx cy)\n  (let* ((translated (geom/transform-polygon polygon 'geom/translate (- cx) (- cy)))\n         (scaled (geom/transform-polygon translated 'geom/dilate scale-factor))\n         (final (geom/transform-polygon scaled 'geom/translate cx cy)))\n    final))\n(scale-from-center '((0 0) (2 0) (2 2) (0 2)) 0.5 1 1)" :note "Scale a polygon from an arbitrary center by composing three transformations: translate to origin, scale, translate back")
  )
  :caveats ("Transform function is passed as a symbol (quoted name), not a function object." "The polygon is transformed point-by-point; geometric properties like area may change (especially with scaling or shearing)." "The order of arguments matters: geom/translate expects (dx dy), geom/rotate expects (degrees), geom/dilate expects (scale)." "Transforms are applied around the origin unless otherwise specified (e.g., geom/rotate-about allows a custom center).")
  :drawbacks ("Only one transformation per call; to combine multiple transforms, chain multiple calls or compose them manually." "No validation that the result is a valid/closed polygon—garbage in, garbage out." "For complex geometric pipelines, building a matrix-based transformation system (e.g., with affine transforms) may be more efficient.")
  :usecases ("Rotating or scaling a sprite or shape for animation." "Reflecting a polygon to test symmetry or create mirrored patterns." "Translating a polygon for collision detection or layout alignment." "Building fractal or tessellation patterns that require repeated transformations.")
  :related ("geom/translate" "geom/rotate" "geom/rotate-about" "geom/dilate" "geom/reflect-x" "geom/reflect-y" "geom/reflect-origin" "geom/reflect-line" "geom/polygon-area" "geom/polygon-perimeter")
  :learn (:concept "Affine transformations applied point-by-point to a polygon." :prerequisites ("Understanding of points and coordinate systems" "Familiarity with at least one basic transformation (translate, rotate, or scale)") :progression "Master individual transformations first (geom/translate, geom/rotate, geom/dilate), then use geom/transform-polygon to apply them systematically. Later explore composition patterns for complex multi-stage transformations.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A designer must apply a translation to every vertex of a decorative shape." :program "(define (shift-shape pts dx dy)
  (geom/transform-polygon pts 'geom/translate dx dy))
(shift-shape '((0 0) (1 0) (1 1) (0 1)) 5 3)" :explanation "Pass the polygon and the transform name (as a symbol); the verb applies pointwise." :meta "geom/transform-polygon is the correct verb because it lifts any per-point transform to a polygon. Manually mapping is possible but this verb centralizes the dispatch.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: pointwise-lift — a scalar/point-level operation is broadcast over a collection."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/transform-polygon '((0 0) (1 0)) 'geom/translate 5 3)")
       (:domain "stamp collection (a metaphor domain — apply the same postmark to every letter in a batch)" :code "(define (postmark letters mark) (list mark letters))")
       (:domain "math — functor lifting an object-level map to a functor-level map" :code "(define (fmap f xs) (map f xs))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung applies a per-element operation across a collection."
     :meta "The shape transfers because map/fmap is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Applying identity as the transform yields the original polygon." :program "(equal? '((1 2) (3 4)) (geom/transform-polygon '((1 2) (3 4)) 'geom/translate 0 0))" :invariant "∀ polygon pts. transform-polygon(pts, geom/translate, 0, 0) = pts" :meta "Identity element of the transform monoid. If broken, the impl mutates on identity. See book-of-math ch 6.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
