(verb
  :name "geom/triangle"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/triangle p1 p2 p3) -> triangle-object"
  :summary "Construct a triangle from three points."
  :explanation "Creates a triangle object (or representation) from three coordinate pairs. This is a foundational constructor for triangle geometry; it does not validate that the points are distinct or non-collinear. Use the result with geom/triangle-area, geom/perimeter, geom/triangle-area-heron, or other triangle verbs to query properties."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/triangle '(0 0) '(3 0) '(0 4))" :note "A right triangle with legs 3 and 4; the result is a triangle object ready for further queries")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define tri (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(4 0) '(2 3)))\n(define area (geom/triangle-area tri))\narea" :note "Construct a triangle, then immediately compute its area using the shoelace formula")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (triangle-properties p1 p2 p3)\n  (let ((tri (geom/triangle p1 p2 p3)))\n    (list (geom/triangle-area tri)\n          (geom/perimeter tri)\n          (geom/angle-between (list (car p1) (cadr p1)) (list (car p3) (cadr p3))))))\n(triangle-properties '(0 0) '(5 0) '(5 12))" :note "Bundle triangle construction with multiple property queries to characterize a triangle fully")
  )
  :caveats ("Three collinear points will produce a degenerate triangle with zero area; no error is raised." "Points must be lists or vectors of exactly two coordinates (x, y); other formats may fail silently." "The triangle object is immutable; to modify it, construct a new triangle.")
  :drawbacks ("geom/triangle itself does no computation; you must call additional verbs (geom/triangle-area, geom/perimeter) to extract properties." "No built-in labeling or naming; if you need to track multiple triangles, manage them manually.")
  :usecases ("Constructing geometric shapes for area or perimeter calculations." "Building polylines or mesh structures that rely on triangles." "Reasoning about angle and distance relationships in a figure." "Testing geometric properties like similarity or congruence.")
  :related ("geom/triangle-area" "geom/triangle-area-heron" "geom/perimeter" "geom/circle" "geom/distance" "geom/collinear?" "geom/similar?")
