(verb
  :name "geom/triangle-area"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/triangle-area triangle) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the area of a triangle using the shoelace formula."
  :explanation "Given a triangle object (constructed with geom/triangle), returns its area as a numeric value. The shoelace formula computes area directly from coordinates without needing side lengths. This is the preferred method when you have the three vertices; for cases where you know only the side lengths, use geom/triangle-area-heron instead."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define tri (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(4 0) '(0 3)))\n(geom/triangle-area tri)" :note "Right triangle with legs 4 and 3 → area = 6")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (verify-area-formula p1 p2 p3)\n  (let ((tri (geom/triangle p1 p2 p3)))\n    (= (geom/triangle-area tri) 6)))\n(verify-area-formula '(0 0) '(3 0) '(0 4))" :note "Check that a 3-4-5 right triangle yields the expected area of 6")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (largest-triangle pts)\n  (fold-left (lambda (acc tri)\n              (if (> (geom/triangle-area tri) (geom/triangle-area acc))\n                tri\n                acc))\n            (car pts)\n            (map (lambda (p) (geom/triangle (car pts) (cadr pts) p)) (cddr pts))))\n(largest-triangle '((0 0) (5 0) (2 8) (3 1) (1 6)))" :note "Find the triangle with the largest area from a list of candidate vertices")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns 0 for degenerate (collinear) triangles; no error is raised." "The result is always non-negative (absolute value is taken internally)." "The shoelace formula is sensitive to the order of vertices; swapping two points may change the sign internally (but abs eliminates this).")
  :drawbacks ("Requires a triangle object (from geom/triangle); if you only have side lengths, use geom/triangle-area-heron instead." "If vertices are very large or very small, floating-point precision may matter.")
  :usecases ("Computing areas of triangular tiles or mesh elements." "Verifying geometric constructions or diagrams." "Comparing sizes of multiple triangles (largest/smallest)." "Spatial partitioning or computational geometry algorithms.")
  :related ("geom/triangle" "geom/triangle-area-heron" "geom/perimeter" "geom/polygon-area" "geom/circle-area")
  :learn (:concept "Shoelace formula for computing area from coordinate geometry." :prerequisites ("2D Cartesian coordinates" "Basic triangle properties (vertices, sides)") :progression "Master geom/triangle-area with coordinates, then learn geom/triangle-area-heron to handle the case where you have side lengths instead. Extend to geom/polygon-area for larger shapes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A world has irregular tiles; the operator needs the area of a specific triangular tile." :program "(define (tile-area tri) (geom/triangle-area tri))
(tile-area (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(4 0) '(0 3)))" :explanation "Apply the shoelace formula to the triangle's vertices." :meta "geom/triangle-area is the correct verb for a coordinate-known triangle. Heron would require converting to side lengths first — wasted work.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: signed-slab sum reduced to a magnitude."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/triangle-area (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(4 0) '(0 3)))")
       (:domain "bookkeeping (a metaphor domain — sum signed transactions, then take absolute value)" :code "(define (net xs) (abs (apply + xs))))")
       (:domain "math — half absolute determinant of edge-vector matrix" :code "(define (half-det a b c) (list a b c))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung sums signed terms then takes an absolute magnitude."
     :meta "The shape transfers because oriented volumes reduce to magnitudes.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Triangle area equals half the base times the height for a right triangle." :program "(define t (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(4 0) '(0 3)))
(< (abs (- (geom/triangle-area t) 6)) 1e-9)" :invariant "for the right triangle with legs a=4, b=3, triangle-area = a·b/2 = 6" :meta "Base-times-height/2 special case. If broken, the coefficient 1/2 is wrong. See book-of-math ch 4 (shoelace formula).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain triangle-area with fold to find the largest triangular tile." :composition "(define (largest-tri tris)
  (fold-left (lambda (acc t)
               (if (> (geom/triangle-area t) (geom/triangle-area acc)) t acc))
             (car tris) (cdr tris)))
(largest-tri (list (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(1 0) '(0 1)) (geom/triangle '(0 0) '(10 0) '(0 10))))" :emergent "reduce-by-measure: pick the largest by a scalar measurement." :meta "Belongs to the family of argmax patterns. See book-of-composition ch 7.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "geom/triangle-area-heron"
  :library "geom"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(geom/triangle-area-heron a b c) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the area of a triangle from three side lengths using Heron's formula."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Direct Heron's-formula computation: s = (a+b+c)/2, area = sqrt(s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)). Clamps the radicand to zero so a degenerate (near-degenerate) triangle returns 0.0 rather than raising on floating-point underflow. Positive-side-length assumption is on the caller."
  :explanation "Given the lengths of three sides (a, b, c), returns the area without needing coordinates. Heron's formula is s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c) where s is the semi-perimeter (a+b+c)/2. This is the dual of geom/triangle-area, used when coordinates are unavailable but side lengths are known. Requires floating-point square roots for the final result."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(geom/triangle-area-heron 3 4 5)" :note "Classic 3-4-5 right triangle. Area = 6. This is the shortest right-triangle with integer sides; the first Pythagorean triple.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "apprentice" :code "(define (equilateral-area side)\n  (geom/triangle-area-heron side side side))\n(equilateral-area 4)" :note "Wrap the three-arg form as a single-arg helper for equilateral triangles. Area of an equilateral with side 4 is 4√3 ≈ 6.928.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (area-from-coords p1 p2 p3)\n  (let ((a (geom/distance p2 p3))\n        (b (geom/distance p1 p3))\n        (c (geom/distance p1 p2)))\n    (geom/triangle-area-heron a b c)))\n(area-from-coords '(0 0) '(3 0) '(0 4))" :note "Convert three vertices to side lengths, then use Heron to compute area. Returns 6 — same as the direct shoelace on this right triangle.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (triangle-inequality? a b c)\n  (and (< a (+ b c)) (< b (+ a c)) (< c (+ a b))))\n(define (safe-area a b c)\n  (if (triangle-inequality? a b c)\n      (geom/triangle-area-heron a b c)\n      'invalid))\n(list (safe-area 3 4 5) (safe-area 1 1 3))" :note "Guard against impossible triangles. (1,1,3) fails the inequality — Heron would return 0 (from the clamp), but 'invalid is more informative to the caller.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "master" :code "(define (parcel-acreage triangles)\n  (let loop ((remaining triangles) (total 0))\n    (if (null? remaining)\n        total\n        (let* ((t (car remaining))\n               (a (car t)) (b (cadr t)) (c (caddr t)))\n          (loop (cdr remaining)\n                (+ total (geom/triangle-area-heron a b c)))))))\n(parcel-acreage '((3 4 5) (5 12 13) (7 24 25)))" :note "Compose Heron across a triangulated parcel to get total surface area. Three Pythagorean triples with legs (3,4), (5,12), (7,24) — areas 6 + 30 + 84 = 120.")
  )
  :caveats ("Requires all three side lengths to be positive numbers." "If the three sides do not satisfy the triangle inequality (sum of any two exceeds the third), the result is 0 (from the clamp) — validate with your own triangle-inequality predicate for stricter callers." "Uses a square-root computation, which may accumulate floating-point error for very large or very small side lengths.")
  :drawbacks ("Heron's formula is less numerically stable than the shoelace formula for extreme coordinates or side lengths; consider using geom/triangle-area (with coordinates) if precision is critical." "Requires that you already know the three side lengths; if you have only coordinates, use geom/triangle-area instead.")
  :usecases ("Computing area when given side lengths (e.g., from a measurement or problem statement)." "Validating that three lengths can form a triangle." "Computing areas in geometry problems that specify only side lengths." "Combining coordinate and distance-based geometry workflows.")
  :related ("geom/triangle-area" "geom/triangle" "geom/distance" "geom/perimeter" "geom/pythagoras-hypotenuse" "geom/pythagoras-leg")
  :learn (:concept "Heron's formula: computing area from side lengths without coordinates." :prerequisites ("Basic triangle properties and the triangle inequality" "Semi-perimeter concept" "Square-root function") :progression "Learn geom/triangle-area first (coordinate-based), then geom/triangle-area-heron to see the side-length version. Practice converting between coordinates and distances with geom/distance.")
  :math (:algebra ("commutative-in-sides") :total #t :domain "three positive reals satisfying triangle inequality" :codomain "non-negative real")
  :cs (:complexity "time O(1), space O(1)" :effects (none) :pure #t)
  :ai (:deterministic #t :cacheable #t :cardinality one :common-mistakes "Passing negative or zero side lengths silently returns 0 (from the sqrt clamp) rather than raising. Callers who need strict input validation should predicate on triangle-inequality? first.")
  :hacker (:primitive #f :history "Heron of Alexandria, ~60 CE. Our impl is the direct sqrt(s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)) form with a max(0, ...) clamp.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "Only the three side lengths of a plot are known; the operator needs its area." :program "(define (side-only-area a b c) (geom/triangle-area-heron a b c))
(side-only-area 3 4 5)" :explanation "Apply Heron's formula. Result is 6 for the 3-4-5 case." :meta "geom/triangle-area-heron is the correct verb when only sides are known. Reconstructing coordinates would require SSS solving first — extra work.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape as triangle-area, but parametrized by sides rather than coordinates."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "geom/*" :code "(geom/triangle-area-heron 3 4 5)")
       (:domain "dispute mediation (a metaphor domain — mediate area of overlap when only edge lengths are witness-reported)" :code "(define (mediate a b c) (list a b c))")
       (:domain "math — s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c) under the sqrt, where s = (a+b+c)/2" :code "(define (heron a b c) (list a b c))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung computes area from three side measurements."
     :meta "The shape transfers because Heron's identity holds in every Euclidean triangle.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Heron is symmetric in the three sides." :program "(< (abs (- (geom/triangle-area-heron 3 4 5) (geom/triangle-area-heron 5 3 4))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ triples (a,b,c). triangle-area-heron(a,b,c) = triangle-area-heron(perm(a,b,c))" :meta "Symmetry under permutation of side arguments. If broken, one side is special. See book-of-math ch 4.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "Chain Heron across a triangulated survey to sum plot area." :composition "(define (survey-area tris)
  (fold-left + 0 (map (lambda (t) (geom/triangle-area-heron (car t) (cadr t) (caddr t))) tris)))
(survey-area '((3 4 5) (5 12 13)))" :emergent "reduce-sum: sum a measurement across a collection." :meta "Belongs to the family of aggregation patterns. See book-of-composition ch 7.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

